<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii 
said wednesday that nato membership for a unified germany should be 
up to the alliance not the soviet union 
but baker said he is willing to consider the kremlins views 
when he meets with soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze 
friday and saturday in bonn 
partly to persuade the soviet union to accept a unified germany 
in nato baker will tell nato foreign ministers that the united 
states will withdraw some nuclear artillery from germany and 
favors prompt negotiations to eliminate other groundbased nuclear 
weapons from europe the washington post said in thursday editions 
while shevardnadze has recently signaled a willingness to drop 
the soviet demand that a unified germany be neutral soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev said last weekend that his countrys 
attitude toward unilateral unbalanced proposals for the entry of 
a future german state into nato remains negative 
west germany is the strongest us ally in the north atlantic 
treaty organization similarly east germany was the staunchest 
soviet ally in the warsaw pact until its conversion to 
westernstyle political democracy earlier this year 
shortly after baker left washington officials of the two german 
states announced a tentative agreement on a plan for merging their 
economies settling basic differences over how the nations should 
assess the costs of unification 
todays agreement announced by officials in east berlin sets 
the stage for a full merger of the economies of the two nations on 
july 2 
west german chancellor helmut kohl has predicted political union 
by the end of 1991 
baker launching a fiveday european trip in which germanys 
future will be the predominant issue said the size of the german 
army is a legitimate topic for eastwest negotiators meeting in 
vienna 
but he said the question whether the unified germany should 
be a member of nato is a question that is properly decided in nato 
with the participation of a united germany 
west germany has become more and more reluctant to be host for 
shortrange nuclear weapons because they would almost inevitably 
explode on german territory if used 
gerhard stoltenberg the west german defense minister said in a 
speech in washington on tuesday that nato might move to get rid of 
all groundbased nuclear weapons leaving only airlaunched 
missiles and bombs in its nuclear arsenal 
according to the international institute for strategic studies 
in london the united states and its allies in 1989 deployed 2872 
artillery pieces in nato theoretically capable of firing nuclear 
shells while warsaw pact powers had 2070 
the united states has been retiring some older 8inch guns 
recently and officials disclosed last month that the pentagon had 
put on hold development of a new edition of the nucleartipped 
lance missile 
the united states has expected to begin talks with the soviet 
union on shortrange nuclear weapons in europe later this year 
after conclusion of an agreement on convention weapons 
baker spoke to reporters aboard his air force jet en route to a 
refueling stop here from washington he then flew to brussels for 
sessions thursday with nato and european community foreign 
ministers 
last saturday the 12nation community took strides toward 
political union by 1993 
france and west germany led the drive britain denmark and 
portugal are hesitant the bush administration has not taken a 
position and baker declined to be drawn into the matter 
baker will fly to bonn on friday for separate sessions with west 
german foreign minister hans dietrich genscher and with 
shevardnadze 
on saturday the foreign ministers of the two germanys and the 
four wartime allies the united states britain france and the 
soviet union will meet 
among the issues baker said they will take up is how to 
relinquish fourpower control of berlin which they have held since 
germanys defeat in 1945 
but germanys membership in nato isnt a proper subject for 
discussion with the soviets baker said 
the fact of the matter is you cant take a decision of that 
nature without having the members of the alliance sitting at the 
table 
at the meeting of the four wartime allies and the two germanys 
there will be indeed a very full and complete discussion of 
that issue because that is one of the foremost issues right now 
that separate the alliance from the position of the soviet union 
baker said 
the prospect of a united and stronger germany in nato has caused 
alarm in moscow and stirred memories of world war ii in which an 
estimated 20 million soviets perished 
at times soviet leaders have called for dissolving both nato 
and the warsaw pact shevardnadze said last week that germany 
should become a testing ground of new forms of eastwest 
security cooperation 
the soviet foreign minister also has floated the idea of the 
unified germany being a member of both alliances the western 
allies meanwhile have suggested keeping nato troops out of what 
is now east germany 
</TEXT>
