<TEXT>
mexican officials on wednesday asked for 
the extradition of a man who says he masterminded the abduction of 
a mexican doctor accused of participating in the death of a us 
drug agent 
mexican attorney general enrique alvarez del castillo said 
extradition papers are being prepared for antonio garate 
bustamante who claims to be a drug enforcement administration 
operative who organized the kidnapping of dr humberto alvarez 
machain in guadalajara on april 2 
us attorney general dick thornburgh met with alvarez del 
castillo for more than an hour discussing drug enforcement efforts 
as well as the current controversy over the alleged abduction of 
alvarez 
we have in process a corresponding arrest order to solicit his 
garates extradition from whichever country he is found 
alvarez del castillo said in spanish after the meeting 
thornburgh refused to say whether alvarez del castillo asked for 
garates extradition during the meeting adding that such requests 
would be made through the us state department 
thornburgh said the matter of alvarez arrest will be dealt with 
during a may 25 federal court hearing in los angeles 
garate a former mexican police officer told the los angeles 
times last week that he arranged the abduction of alvarez with 
approval from the dea garate said 10 mexicans were promised 
100000 for alvarez capture and delivery to el paso texas 
according to the times 
earlier a spokesman for alvarez del castillo fernando arias 
alvarez said mexico would ask for the extradition of others who 
may have participated in the abduction of alvarez 
one of five men arrested in the abduction placed garate at the 
scene arias said that man jorge cobarrubias an expoliceman 
from the mexican state of hidalgo said he lined up the others to 
help grab the doctor said arias 
the abduction of the doctor has strained relations between the 
united states and mexico which has threatened to stop cooperating 
in the fight against drug trafficking 
arias also said that mexico wants an agreement with the united 
states that would allow mexican drug agents to operate in the 
united states the same way us dea agents work in mexico there 
are 41 dea agents in mexico he said 
the two countrys ambassadors john negroponte of the united 
states and gustavo petricioli of mexico were at wednesdays 
meeting which was held as a threeday conference of border state 
attorneys general began in santa fe arias said 
the two attorneys general were talking about possible formal 
charges against garate and others arias said 
alvarez a guadalajara gynecologist is charged in connection 
with the 1985 death of drug agent enrique camarena prosecutors 
allege that alvarez gave camarena drugs to revive him for 
additional torture before his slaying 
his trial has been delayed pending a courtordered may 25 
hearing in us district court in los angeles on the matter of how 
he was brought to the us from mexico 
</TEXT>
