<TEXT>
the post office is proposing a 
revolutionary idea that the 150 million people of latin americas 
largest country pay their bills by mail instead of standing in line 
brazil is modern in many ways but you still cannot write a 
check for your electricity bill put it in a stamped envelope and 
drop it in a mailbox 
virtually all bills are paid at banks which are clogged with 
long lines of grumbling sweaty people holding stacks of 
electricity gas and water bills school department store health 
insurance and credit card accounts auto license fees and 
statements of income or property taxes 
a specialized commercial culture has sprouted around the 
practice companies and wealthy individuals hire young men 
universally called office boys to do their standing and paying 
one companys office boy presented a check to pay the telephone 
bill but the bank insisted on cash he went to the companys own 
bank which said it would take a check but must have a new one 
naming the bank as payee in desperation the office boy returned 
to the first bank where the manager finally made an exception and 
accepted the check 
the post office wants to make things simpler 
its press spokesman jose valfranio medeiros de oliveira said 
in an interview theres nothing easier than paying bills by 
mail and we want to make life easier for our citizens 
some newspapers have begun rather timidly to support the 
program 
yes there is a long tradition here of not paying by mail 
oliveira said but we have the infrastructure we have 
credibility theres no reason this wont work 
this month he said the post office will run a test program 
allowing people in the northeastern state of bahia population 116 
million to pay telephone bills by mail if that goes well the 
experiment will be extended to other states and to bills for water 
gas and federal taxes 
all brazils 4000plus townships have post offices whereas 
onethird dont have banks oliveira said 
in addition there are 22000 public mailboxes and 3000 rural 
collection points on farms and ranches post offices have longer 
hours than banks some post offices are open on weekends 
brazils largest commercial bank the governmentcontrolled 
banco do brasil announced plans for a citizens comfort a 
program that would allow even people without accounts at the bank 
to mail it their checks for water electricity gas and federal tax 
bills 
alberto policaro the bank president said that would make life 
easier for brazilians and free bank workers from receiving bills 
and let them get on with the banks real business taking in 
deposits and making loans 
public acceptance of such a departure is far from universal 
luis santanna mendes a rio teletype operator who used to work 
for the post office telegraph service said id rather wait in 
line at a bank that way you have confirmation that you paid 
at a bank you get a stub with a machine stamp showing the 
amount paid 
oliveira said post offices could provide the same kind of 
receipt that means bill payers would have to line up at the post 
office of course but the press spokesman said our lines move 
faster than bank lines 
surveys by brazils largest private polling company known as 
ibope indicate the post office is brazils most trusted public 
institution but skepticism persists 
you just dont know if the letter really will get there 
mendes said 
another problem is that brazilian banks do not return canceled 
checks they keep check records on microfilm in the case of a 
disputed payment the payer would have to line up at the bank to 
see his account record 
there are technical details to be worked out oliveira 
acknowledged but if you can pay bills by mail in the united 
states and europe theres no reason you cant do it in brazil 
too 
</TEXT>
