<TEXT>
looks arent everything if they were zoo 
curators across the country wouldnt be scrambling to get their own 
colonies of naked mole rats 
the fanged 4inch african mammals are desired for their 
subterranean social habits not their pink wrinkled looks 
theyre not the most attractive mammal ive ever seen said 
james doherty general curator at new yorks bronx zoo which plans 
to open an exhibit next winter 
since march 1989 the cincinnati zoo has had the nations only 
display of the hairless mole rats but the brookfield zoo near 
chicago plans to open its exhibit may 18 zoos in philadelphia and 
london have mole rats that are not on display while zoos in phoenix 
and washington dc are seeking colonies 
it continues to be a popular attraction because they catch 
your eye for one reason or another said randy morgan an 
entomologist who oversees the cincinnati zoos 40rat exhibit i 
dont think of them as ugly i think they come across as bizarre 
animated and comical 
zoo curators and scientists say mole rats beauty and 
significance are in their lifestyles virtually blind they live 
underground and burrow in a constant search for food tubers and 
roots they find by stumbling upon them 
however they are distinguished by their social system morgan 
said tuesday 
they live in colonies of about three dozen only one female in 
each colony breeds using her sharp teeth to fend off challengers 
and secreting a scent that inhibits other females from developing 
into queens 
only one or two males mate with the queen and researchers are 
uncertain how they are selected morgan said all other ablebodied 
mole rats search for food for themselves and the queen 
in exhibits they scamper backward as easily as forward yanking 
other mole rats out of the way by their tails and digging through 
wood and cork shavings within their home 
they sleep in huddles piling on top of each other for warmth 
but a pile of naked mole rats is seldom still if one twitches in 
its sleep the entire huddle shudders morgan said 
documented more than a century ago naked mole rats are found 
only under the desert of kenya in eastern africa zoos pay about 
200 an animal said bruce brewer curator of mammals at the 
brookfield zoo 
zoo curators credit south african researcher jennifer jarvis 
with bringing mole rats to light which piqued zoos interest 
the problem with zoo displays was the mole rats extreme 
sensitivity to sound and vibration doherty said the rats are 
easily panicked by the slightest sound or vibration and their huge 
incisors can rapidly scratch plexiglass into a frosted opaque 
shield 
we kind of whisper around them doherty said 
zoos have developed ways to shockproof their mole rat habitats 
some building mazes of glass tubes on tables embedded in sand and 
others erecting double glass walls that trap air as insulation 
reaction from zoo patrons varies when they first see naked mole 
rats morgan said 
it varies from oh yuck to oh my god morgan said they 
see mole or rat on the display and think these are the things in 
my front yard 
but for people who take time to read about them they are 
amazed he said on busy days people are lined up three to 
four deep 
</TEXT>
