<TEXT>
oriental food is king in this queen city 
of the ozarks where even the burger joints serve the dish that all 
springfield craves cashew chicken 
ozark cuisine may conjure up images of panfried trout and 
catfish fried chicken mashed potatoes and gravy but just as 
surely as bostonians bake beans and chicagoans take pride in pizza 
springfields culinary claim to fame is cashew chicken 
more than 50 of springfields 375 licensed restaurants feature 
chinese food another dozen or so korean polynesian japanese and 
vietnamese restaurants contribute to a gastronomic smorgasbord for 
asian food lovers 
im a chinese food nut with a chinese restaurant on every 
corner im in heaven says gary wilson an attorney and regular 
at the allyoucaneat noon and evening buffets offered by many of 
the restaurants 
but not just any chinese food chinese restaurants here are 
judged not for their moo goo gai pan or egg rolls but for their 
cashew chicken and not just chinese restaurants even cafeterias 
and burger shops serve up the dish 
springfields unofficial nickname says it all cashew chicken 
capital of the midwest 
one newspaper columnist took calculator in hand and figured that 
springfield restaurants serve a minimum of 6697 to 8554 orders of 
cashew chicken a day that averages out to 24 million to 31 
million orders a year 
springfields variation on the dish isnt the standard cashew 
chicken dish found around the country where stirfried chicken and 
vegetables are mixed with cashews 
chefs here dip the chicken in batter deepfat fry it smother 
it with a thick brown sauce made from chicken stock and soy sauce 
add cashews and a few bits of green onion and serve the concoction 
beside a bed of fried rice 
one aficionado fondly describes the meal as kind of like 
chicken mcnuggets with gravy 
so peculiar is the cashew chicken recipe to springfield that 
chinese restaurants in cities like dallas chicago kansas city and 
st louis that try to imitate it identify the dish on menus as 
springfield cashew chicken 
but the cashew chicken served outside of springfield a regional 
trade and health center in southwestern missouri usually falls 
short of the dish current and former residents crave 
ive never tasted the cashew chicken i loved in springfield 
anywhere else says timolyn skeeters a flight attendant based in 
charlotte nc and a graduate of southwest missouri state 
university in springfield i miss it out here cashew chicken is 
just regular chicken and a few cashews i think the secret must be 
in the sauce 
the roots of springfields love affair with cashew chicken can 
be traced to 1963 
that was when david leong and his wife shau left florida to 
found leongs tea house springfields first chinese restaurant at 
first ozarkers were skeptical of chinese food 
my father noticed that people here liked fried chicken said 
ling leong president of his familys restaurant and chinese 
specialty foods company so he cut it into bitesize pieces and 
served it with a special sauce and cashews and rice 
springfield cashew chicken was born and quickly became a hit 
among the meatandpotatoes crowd 
soon more chinese then vietnamese began moving to springfield 
where minorities still account for barely 2 percent of the 
population they opened restaurants and virtually every one 
featured cashew chicken 
i think one reason cashew chicken became popular is because 
this is chicken country said woodrow sun who with his wife 
aurora owns four chinese restaurants people like to eat 
chicken eighty percent of my restaurants sales are chicken 
dishes 
the low price of cashew chicken ranging from about 250 for a 
carryout order to around 7 in fullservice restaurants appeals 
to families and the 25000 students attending four colleges in the 
city 
leong said hed heard two more chinese restaurants would open 
this year 
if they asked me my advice would be dont do it sun said 
with a wry smile thats all this town needs is another chinese 
restaurant 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

