<TEXT>
the pentagon touting the contribution its new 
radar could make in the drug war is seeking money for the 
hightech system that congress wouldnt buy for its military value 
the 2428 million radar which would scan deep into mexico to 
find drugsmuggling aircraft has resurfaced as the costliest item 
in the defense departments 1991 counterdrug budget 
congressional investigators question whether moving the system 
to the popular and growing antidrug budget is a maneuver to save 
it 
i categorically deny it said michael a wermuth deputy 
assistant secretary of defense for drug enforcement policy 
the defense department tried to sell a southernfacing sector of 
over the horizon backscatter radar to congress in fiscal years 
1989 and 1990 citing a potential bomber threat from latin america 
but lawmakers such as rep nicholas mavroules dmass chairman 
of the house armed services investigations subcommittee were 
unconvinced and declined to approve the project 
mavroules said there was absolutely not in my judgment a 
bomber threat from latin america the lawmaker said he wants to 
investigate the budget shuffle but is willing to let the pentagon 
prove the radar is an effective tool in drug interdiction 
the first backscatter system became operational april 24 in 
bangor maine to protect the atlantic coast wermuth said test 
results showed it could detect the slowmoving lowflying drug 
planes that plod toward the us southwest border 
other backscatter sites are under construction in the west 
and congress also has agreed to construction of the radar in alaska 
this is not a system that has been purchased exclusively for 
counternarcotics said the pentagons wermuth arguing there 
still is a longterm bomber threat from the south even if theres 
no current threat from latin america 
he said the southernlooking sector of backscatter was moved 
to the drug budget in recognition of the contribution that part 
of the system will make in the counternarcotics effort 
the centralsouthwest sector of backscatter comprises 
onefifth of the pentagons 12 billion antidrug budget for the 
coming fiscal year this year the military is expected to spend 
887 million to combat illegal drugs wermuth said 
a house armed services committee staff member familiar with the 
decision not to fund the southernbeamed radar said skepticism 
about a bomber threat from latin america was the dominant reason 
the project was not approved 
the staffer who spoke on condition of anonymity said it is a 
common ploy of the pentagon to transfer controversial programs into 
the sacred cow of the day right now its drugs 
it raises the question of whether its just a shuffle to get a 
system that may not be justified to meet a military threat said 
louis rodrigues who is directing a general accounting office 
investigation into the radar systems costeffectiveness 
the investigation was requested by the senate armed services 
committee 
if backscatter works as planned it would be able to spot 
even the smallest smuggler aircraft somewhere over mexico long 
before it reached the border 
the hightech system bounces powerful radio beams off the 
ionosphere unlike conventional radars whose beams are limited to 
line of sight return signals reach massive antennas and generate 
computer radar pictures of targets between 500 and 2000 miles 
distant 
pentagon officials say the systems computers then would be able 
to feed tactical information on drug targets to law enforcement 
intelligence centers 
the centralsouthwest sector would be located in north dakota 
south dakota and minnesota 
</TEXT>
