<TEXT>
in a village in kosovo province 
tens of thousands of ethnic albanians gathered to formally renounce 
the practice of seeking blood vengeance against rival families 
tanjug reported 
the previously unannounced gathering tuesday proceeded without 
major incidents or police intervention the state news agency said 
kosovo repeatedly has seen clashes between the southern 
provinces ethnic albanian majority which seeks greater autonomy 
and massive security forces sent in to protect the slav minority 
from alleged albanian harassment 
tanjug said the ethnic albanians waved flags without the 
communist symbol of a fivepointed star and shouted at any member 
of kosovos serb minority passing by 
the gathering in the village of gornja luka close to 
neighboring communist albania was the second such meeting in the 
past month in kosovo 
the tradition of blood vengeance dates from the middle ages 
and binds the head of an ethnic albanian family to claim blood if a 
family member is attacked by any member of a rival family 
reconciliation is usually completed with the head of the family 
claiming blood vowing not to seek fresh blood women are exempt 
from blood vengeance and traditionally have taken over the field 
work of any male relatives who feared their lives were in danger 
and thus stayed inside family quarters 
tanjug estimated tuesdays crowd at 100000 other sources who 
asked not to be identified estimated the number at tens of 
thousands 
tanjug said thousands of car tractors trucks buses and cattle 
drawn carts clogged the roads around gornja luka from early morning 
until early afternoon 
staterun television and radio made no mention of the ceremony 
and it was not clear how many ethnic albanian families buried their 
feuds at the gathering 
</TEXT>
