<TEXT>
joe schock is still on the lam two 
decades after fleeing charges that he torched 29 national guard 
trucks and jeeps in reaction to the killing of four vietnam war 
protesters at kent state university 
yet after an odyssey through the radical underground schocks 
life has evolved into an existence similar to that he fled today 
he is a paunchy suburban father of two daughters teaching english 
to young accountants in paris 
and much to the sorrow of his family the 42yearold fugitive 
vows never to return to the united states 
ive gone down another road he said in a recent telephone 
interview with the idahonian newspaper in moscow idaho i dont 
feel good about the states i dont want to readapt 
he is a free man in france shielded from us authorities by a 
treaty that bars the extradition of political fugitives he has 
become a french citizen 
schock served as a marine in vietnam but he returned with 
growing doubts about his countrys role his skepticism intensified 
after he joined antiwar groups at idaho and washington state 
universities 
on may 4 1970 his parents and police say the deaths at kent 
state led him to go to the lewiston armory with boltcutters and 
gasoline 
he told me where the wire cutters and gloves were left where 
he left them said ed schock his father i cant say if he was 
alone but i think he did it 
police said a witness saw schock toss an object over the armory 
fence and run moments after a thunderous explosion schock flagged 
down a car but he was arrested at a roadblock his clothes reeking 
of gasoline police said 
schock neither denies nor admits involvement with the sabotage 
some day i still may have to defend myself in a us court he 
said 
he fled the country in july 1970 while awaiting trial on federal 
charges of destruction of property his family did not hear from 
him for two years 
schocks sister lois gibbens of pasco wash has not seen him 
since he left his parents have visited him in france three times 
its a tragedy in our family gibbens said 
her brother agreed my family most certainly has suffered from 
my problems 
but schock insisted he would not come home even if charges were 
not hanging over him 
if they could give me a job in lewiston at 200000 a year i 
wouldnt want to come home he said i dont want to be 
dominated by that economic system 
although a judge dismissed the indictment against schock in 
1979 prosecutors say it was merely a housekeeping chore to clear 
the books of old cases prosecutors and schocks lawyer carl 
maxey agreed that charges could easily be reinstated 
the charges carry up to 10 years in prison and a 10000 fine 
schock said he would not be received warmly by most americans if 
he came home 
theyd still hold it against me he said they wouldnt 
justify that kind of action 
