<TEXT>
finding ways to prevent and treat diseases 
that disable the elderly can provide a cushion in the next century 
when aging baby boomers are expected to push health care costs into 
the sky researchers say 
while medical advances are keeping americans alive longer this 
may mean that more people will be at risk of becoming disabled in 
late life by such conditions as alzheimers disease and hip 
fractures 
we cant afford not to invest more now in research on aging 
said dr edward l schneider dean of the university of southern 
californias andrus gerontology center and coauthor of a study on 
the impact of aging baby boomers could have on the nations 
heathcare system 
the study reported in this weeks journal of the american 
medical association projected that medicare expenditures which 
were 71 billion in 1987 could soar as high as 212 billion in 
2040 when the average age of a baby boomer is 85 
medicare costs for those 85 and older the fastest growing 
segment of the us population could grow sixfold the study said 
nursing home costs now 31 billion for 13 million patients 
could rise to as much as 139 billion with 59 million people 
living in these facilities the study estimated 
the number of americans with conditions like alzheimers disease 
and hip fractures caused by osteoporosis two of the biggest 
contributors to nursing home admissions could quadruple unless 
ways are found to prevent or delay the onset of these conditions 
the study said 
research is also needed for other diseases that afflict the 
elderly including parkinsons disease osteoarthritis and vision 
and hearing ailments researchers said 
this is where the challenge of aging research lies said 
dr jack m guralnik an epidemiologist at the governments 
national institute on aging and coauthor of the report 
cost containment will not be enough to offset the huge increases 
in health care that will be needed in the next century the 
researchers said 
the greatest savings will be found in preventing and delaying 
the onset of the debilitating diseases that rob the elderly of 
their independence and force them to rely on others for care they 
said 
a 1 billion annual investment in alzheimers research would 
likely yield advances that could at least delay the onset of the 
disease by a minimum of five years which would save 500 billion 
in care costs in the two decades from 20002020 schneider said 
the federal government is spending about 148 million this year 
to research alzheimers disease the most common form of dementia 
in the last 100 years we have extended life expectancy 29 
years but weve done precious little research into how to make 
those last 29 years quality years sen tom harkin diowa said 
at a briefing where the study was released on tuesday 
harkin chairman of the senate appropriations subcommittee that 
deals with medical research said he will introduce legislation to 
increase federal financing of aging research from the current 400 
million to 1 billion annually 
were either going to invest now or pay later he said 
joseph califano jr once secretary of the old department of 
health education and welfare and a national spokesman for project 
independence for older americans said the study findings show that 
the most costeffective research the united states can put money 
into now is in aging research 
</TEXT>
