hundreds of antigovernment protesters 
continued to occupy a downtown square today and the countrys 
interim leadership tried to defuse a threat by opposition parties 
to boycott elections later this month 
about 500 antigovernment demonstrators occupied university 
square in an ongoing protest that entered its 11th day today the 
protesters are demanding that interim president ion iliescu resign 
because of his communist past 
their ranks included 25 demonstrators who have vowed to continue 
a hunger strike until iliescu steps down seventeen of the hunger 
strikers said they have only taken sips of tea since they began 
their fast monday night eight others joined the fast later 
i will continue until i die said viorel popa a 25yearold 
worker from the southwestern town of turnu severin who was among 
the group of hunger strikers huddled under the balcony of a 
bucharest university building 
the oldest hunger striker 66yearold nicolae bucsenescu said 
we will not give up until the clique of reds is removed 
the protest has also caused a diplomatic row with france the 
government officially protested today the actions of two french 
parliament members who addressed the crowd on university square on 
tuesday 
the university square protest which has occurred virtually 
roundtheclock since april 22 is the most visible against the 
interim government as the country prepares for its first free 
elections in more than 50 years on may 20 
five major opposition parties threatened on monday to boycott 
the elections saying more time is needed to prepare for the vote 
they accused iliescus national salvation front which dominates 
the provisional governing coalition of monopolizing power 
on tuesday the interim government guaranteed equal chances to 
all parties contesting the election and offered to meet the 
opposition parties to discuss their criticisms 
the government said claims that the front was harassing 
opposition activists and using facilities left by the deposed 
communist party can be discussed with representatives of the 
government to eliminate any kind of suspicions and to improve 
some organizational aspects of the elections 
the opposition parties which repeatedly have accused the front 
of using public funds for electioneering and unfairly dominating 
the national media had no immediate reaction to the government 
statement 
on tuesday 8000 anticommunist protesters gathered in 
