<TEXT>
china has been authorized to buy an additional 
2 million metric tons of us wheat at subsidized prices the 
agriculture department announced today 
undersecretary richard t crowder said the wheat will be 
available to china under the departments export enhancement 
program or eep a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 
367 bushels of wheat 
the new subsidy line was on top of 5050 tons left from an eep 
allocation of 1 million tons made on feb 8 since the subsidy 
program began five years ago china has used it to buy about 152 
million tons of us wheat exceeded only by the soviet union at 
208 million tons 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
the subsidies have averaged from around 4 per ton to more than 
40 per ton of wheat or in the range of 11 cents to about 110 
per bushel 
purchases of us wheat for 198990 delivery total about 57 
million tons much of it without subsidies in 198889 china 
bought nearly 81 million tons all of it carrying eep subsidies 
chinas wheat orders under the program for the 199091 marketing 
year that will begin june 1 are reported at 1 million tons 
