<DOCNO> AP900502-0084 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
legislators at an international conference on 
the environment today passed a resolution calling for nations to 
commit themselves to a 50 percent total reduction in globalwarming 
pollutants over the next 20 years 
the legislators from 42 nations also called for other steppedup 
efforts to deal with the environment including creation of a 
global marshall plan to help developing countries cope with 
environmental concerns 
the threeday conference concluded with overwhelming approval of 
a reduction timetable for globalwarming pollutants pushed by the 
us congressional delegation which hosted the conference 
the resolution contrasts with bush administration policy which 
has advocated more research before specific pollution controls are 
proclaimed 
the resolutions and goals approved by the interparliamentary 
conference on the global environment are not binding on any nation 
but some participants said they hoped to use the conference report 
to sway fellow legislators back home about the need to take 
specific actions on environmental matters 
i hope that this is going to be the beginning the beginning 
in which we can have a global survival dialogue attiya 
inayatullah a member of the parliament of pakistan told reporters 
more than 200 lawmakers from 42 nations including the soviet 
union most european countries japan and many developing nations 
participated in the conference 
the conference agreed to establish a broad range of 
environmental goals including actions aimed at protecting the 
ozone layer reversing the loss of forests and committing greater 
resources to population control 
the policy statements however provided few specifics on how 
some of these efforts would be funded including the proposed plan 
by industrial nations to help developing countries deal with the 
environment 
this socalled global marshall plan for sustainable 
development and the environment would be patterned on the 
postworld war ii economic assistance efforts by the united states 
that help european recover from the war officials said 
sen albert gore dtenn one of the organizers and other us 
delegates had pushed for a consensus in a closing policy 
declaration that the time to act is now to deal with such 
issues as global warming 
one resolution that was approved calls for immediate action on 
setting specific goals for reducing manmade pollutants including 
carbon dioxide that cause global warming or the greenhouse effect 
delay exposes us our children and their children to 
calamities which we will have made irrevocable by inaction in the 
present the draft resolution declared 
the strong statement for action drafted by the us delegates 
to the conference is in sharp contrast to the bush 
administrations position that additional research into global 
warming and its potential economic impact is needed before specific 
pollution curbs should be set in concrete 
nevertheless gore and sen john chafee rri stressed that 
the gathering was not intended to embarrass president bush two 
weeks ago he caused rumblings among delegates to a white house 
conference on global warming by emphasizing the need for study over 
development of specific response strategies 
in contrast the legislative delegates drafted a globalwarming 
resolution that scarcely refers to the need for more research and 
calls for setting a timetable for specific cuts in global warming 
pollutants by the year 2010 
the resolution calls for a roughly 20 percent reduction in 
carbon dioxide a product of burning fossil fuels total 
elimination of chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs and a variety of other 
ozonedepleting chemicals and a 10 percent reduction in methane 
emissions 
altogether that would amount to about a 50 percent reduction in 
globalwarming pollutants by 2010 
</TEXT>
