<TEXT>
maronite catholic religious leaders 
appealed for a maritime ceasefire wednesday as rival christian 
forces fired on passenger ferries near each others ports 
police said no casualties were reported in the latest round of 
fighting 
the ferries which operate out of cyprus provide the only 
regular link to the outside world for christians trapped in their 
310squaremile enclave north of beirut which is ringed by hostile 
syrian troops and their mainly moslem militia allies 
on wednesday rebel troops loyal to gen michel aoun and the 
lebanese forces militia led by samir geagea continued their 
maritime battle the latest flareup in their 3monthold power 
struggle for control of the christian enclave 
a police spokesman said an armed speedboat manned by lebanese 
forces militiamen intercepted the virgin butterly a hydrofoil 
ferry before dawn wednesday off of aouns only sea outlet the 
makeshift port of dbaye seven miles north of beirut 
the spokesman who cannot be identified under existing 
regulations said the militiamen did not try to seize the 
hydrofoil but fired warning shots from a 145mm machine gun to 
prevent it from heading for aouns port 
the spokesman said the virgin butterfly was not hit by the 
gunfire but sailed back to the cyprian port of larnaca 
aouns gunners responded by shelling another ferry the sunny 
boat as it waited to pick up passengers in the geageacontrolled 
port of jounieh five miles north of dbaye 
the sunny boat raced for the open sea as shells exploded in the 
water around it the police spokesman said there were no reports 
that the ship had been hit 
the maritime fighting has flared up since geagea imposed a naval 
blockade april 23 on the threemile stretch of coast controlled by 
aoun in a bid to prevent seaborne supplies of weapons and 
ammunition from reaching the generals forces 
geageas militia with 6000 fighters and 30000 reservists has 
one gunboat and about 20 speedboats armed with machine guns and 
rocket launchers 
aouns 19000man army lost most of its naval force when 
geageas forces seized the naval base at jounieh in february the 
general has two crippled gunboats trapped near dbaye 
the ferry attacks prompted maronite catholic religious leaders 
to seek a maritime ceasefire 
to that end bulos naaman former head of the order of maronite 
monks met with aoun and planned to see geagea later radio 
stations reported 
naaman refused to comment to reporters after his meeting with 
aoun 
by police count 920 people have been killed and 2448 wounded 
since jan 30 when the inconclusive battle began between geageas 
militia and aouns troops the worst conflict between christians in 
lebanons 15yearold civil war 
aoun has refused to recognize the syrianbacked government of 
president elias hrawi objecting to the 40000 syrian troops in 
lebanon geagea supports the hrawi government 
on wednesday the rival christian forces dueled with howitzers 
and mortars in east beirut and kesrouan province to the north 
but the fighting did not spread to the shellshattered resort 
town of kleiat in the mountains northeast of beirut where civilians 
have staged a sitin under a huge tent in the main square to 
protest further violence 
the sitin began tuesday evening after the expiration of an 
81hour ceasefire called by the maronite church to allow local 
townspeople to salvage what was left of their property 
