<TEXT>
the doortodoor portion of the 1990 census 
spreads out to the nations smaller cities and towns thursday 
census workers who began their household count in 110 larger 
cities april 26 are expanding to the remaining 374 census districts 
across the country according to bureau spokesman ray bancroft 
only about 63 percent of the nations households have returned 
census forms mailed in late march the bureau had hoped for a 70 
percent response and the shortfall will raise the price of the 
count by millions of dollars because of the expanded doortodoor 
effort 
the national count every 10 years is required by the 
constitution for use in reapportioning seats in the house of 
representatives the figures also are used to apportion seats in 
state legislatures and divide hundreds of billions of dollars in 
federal and state aid 
minority groups say past counts have missed more poor and 
minorities than whites and higher income people 
lower educational and income levels larger household sizes and 
the more frequent presence of distant relatives in households are 
major factors in these undercounts population analyst david j 
fein said in demography the journal of the population association 
of america 
fein of abt associates in bethesda md estimated that as many 
as 15 percent of puerto ricans 12 percent of blacks and 9 percent 
of mexican americans were omitted in the 1980 census 
census bureau figures were lower than that but the agency did 
estimate that while it missed about 14 percent of all americans 
the rate may have been as high as 6 percent for young black men 
the possibility of adjusting the 1990 figures to account for 
this undercount has been proposed and debated by politicians and 
statisticians the commerce department parent agency of the census 
bureau has said it is trying to do a complete count and will 
consider adjustment only after the basic census effort is done 
a coalition of cities and interest groups has filed suit against 
the bureau seeking to force a statistical adjustment of the final 
census figures 
forms for millions of americans were delayed by addressing 
mistakes while millions of others simply havent mailed theirs 
back the problems including large apartment buiildings and whole 
blocks and small towns seemingly overlooked have drawn heavy 
criticism for the census bureau 
in the last few decades the system of mailing census 
questionnaires and asking people to return them has become common 
practice it replaced the traditional but laborintensive process 
of having someone visit every home 
now the doortodoor count is reserved for sparsely populated 
areas and followup on people who dont answer by mail 
originally expected to cost 13 billion this year the price of 
counting americans could well increase by 180 million or more 
according to congressional sources 
in rural areas which were not included in the mailed portion of 
the count personal visits by census takers have been going on 
since march 
</TEXT>
