<TEXT>
a house ways and means subcommittee voted 
wednesday to allow people aged 65 through 69 to earn more money 
without losing any of their social security benefits 
a bill approved by the social security subcommittee also 
includes a provision removing the social security administration 
from the department of health and human services and creating it as 
an independent agency that provision is opposed by the bush 
administration 
the legislation also would require the social security 
administration to improve telephone access to local offices the 
administration cut local telephone service last year preferring to 
rely on a nationwide tollfree number for most beneficiary problems 
the proposed increase in the amount social security recipients 
may earn without losing benefits is considerably less generous than 
taxwriting committees of the house and senate approved last year 
congressional republicans have made outright repeal of the earnings 
limitation a top goal contending it reduces incentives for older 
americans to work 
present law allows a person aged 65 through 69 to earn up to 
9360 this year without penalty each 3 earned above that amount 
reduces social security benefits by 1 
an automatic inflation adjustment built into the law will raise 
the limit to 9960 next year and to 10440 in 1992 the bill 
approved without dissent by the subcommittee would raise the 
figures to 10200 in 1991 and 10920 in 1992 
the bill makes no change in the 6840 earnings limit on people 
under age 65 neither does it affect those 70 or older they could 
continue to earn an unlimited amount without losing any social 
security benefit 
</TEXT>
