<TEXT>
leftist guerrillas dynamited 
power stations and attacked strategic targets in the capital early 
today to protest human rights violations they blame on the armed 
forces 
the attacks began shortly before midnight tuesday and faded 
after several hours of predawn fighting the armed forces said it 
suffered five dead and six wounded and that 12 civilians were also 
wounded 
half the city was without electricity and automatic weapons fire 
and explosions ripped through several neighborhoods including the 
wealthy escalon district 
rebels had dynamited five highvoltage utility towers and a 
power plant on nearby san salvador volcano the privately owned 
yskl radio station reported 
there was no fighting in the capital during the morning but 
skirmishing was reported in several areas outside the capital 
including the town of ilobasco 40 miles to the northeast no 
casualty figures were available 
the attacks were a protest of the total immunity that exists 
in this country for members of the armed forces who violate human 
rights the farabundo marti national liberation front guerrillas 
said in a statement sent by fascimile 
the statement cited the stalled investigation and evident 
coverup of the intellectual authors of the crime against the 
jesuits referring to the killings of six jesuit priests at 
central american university in november 
president alfredo cristiani has admitted the six priests 
including the university rector were killed by members of the 
armed forces but critics have said the investigation should go 
farther 
one high officer col guillermo benavides has been charged in 
the killings of the jesuits along with three lieutenants and five 
soldiers 
despite years of deathsquad killings no officer has ever been 
convicted in a human rightsrelated crime 
the house foreign affairs committee voted last week to cut us 
military aid to el salvador in half from 85 million the other 
half would be cut if the government fails to properly investigate 
the jesuit killings or negotiate in good faith with the guerrillas 
the attacks also appeared timed to coincide with the scheduled 
start of preliminary peace talks today 
indirect preliminary talks were to begin today between 
cristianis rightist government and the guerrillas 
a presidential spokesman said a representative of un 
generalsecretary javier perez de cuellar was expected to arrive 
today to act as a gobetween in setting up an agenda and arranging 
other details for the negotiations 
the guerrilla statement said they were still disposed to 
continue with the negotiating process 
the first guerrilla attack on the power line towers began at 
about 10 pm tuesday hours after about 40000 people attended a 
huge may day rally organized by labor unions and opposition parties 
to criticize cristianis economic austerity program and urge peace 
talks 
at the peaceful rally militant leftists joined the moderate 
christian democrats whom cristiani succeeded in one of the largest 
opposition protests in a decade 
guerrillas shot it out with government soldiers near the hotel 
in escalon where americans had been trapped for a time during the 
november offensive and the gunfight spilled over into the tasumal 
neighborhood residents there said 
attempts to negotiate an end to the war ended in deadlock in 
1984 and 1985 and a series of direct talks began shortly after 
cristiani was sworn in as president in july 
they broke off as a result of the monthlong november offensive 
more than 72000 people have been killed most of them 
civilians since the war began in october 1979 
