<TEXT>
orders to factories for manufactured goods 
have rebounded from januarys worst decline in 16 years the 
government said wednesday in a report analysts interpreted as 
another sign the industrial sector is recovering from months of 
weakness 
the commerce department said orders for both durable and 
nondurable goods rose 38 percent in march to a seasonally 
adjusted 2404 billion after advancing 18 percent in february 
and thus recovered from the 55 percent decline in january 
robert g dederick chief economist with the northern trust co 
in chicago said the weakness is behind us and we now have a 
flat slightly upward bias 
i think the worst is over said allen sinai chief economist 
for the boston co the question now is what kind of rebound and 
whether the longterm interest spike over the last month or so 
will abort what appears to be a recovery 
the january drop was the steepest since a 7 percent decline in 
december 1974 the march increase was the largest since a 47 
percent gain in december 1988 
the department said most of the overall march increase was in 
durable goods up 66 percent to 1287 billion after a 24 percent 
increase the previous month 
durable goods bigticket items expected to last more than 
three years have borne the brunt of high interest rates since 
they often are financed through loans 
but most of the durable goods increase was concentrated in the 
transportation category it was up 224 percent to 366 billion 
due in large part to a 632 percent increase in aircraft orders 
transportation orders had risen 101 percent in february 
excluding transportation orders were up 1 percent 
other durable goods categories posting gains were primary 
metals up 73 percent to 117 billion after a 42 percent decline 
in february and nonelectrical machinery up 12 percent to 226 
billion after falling 06 percent in february 
electrical machinery orders on the other hand fell 16 percent 
to 196 billion after rising 28 percent the previous month 
nondurable goods orders also rose up 08 percent to 1117 
billion on top of a 11 percent gain the previous month food and 
chemicals accounted for most of the advance 
in the key category of nondefense capital goods a barometer of 
business investment plans orders advanced 144 percent to 413 
billion after declines of 59 percent in february and 136 percent 
in january 
but defense orders dropped 39 percent to 74 billion after 
jumping 183 percent in february excluding defense orders gained 
4 percent the largest such increase since a similar advance in 
april 1989 
the department also said shipments were up 11 percent to 2368 
billion after gaining 34 percent a month earlier they were the 
first backtoback gains since january 1989 
inventories fell 03 percent to 3719 billion their third 
decline in four months 
inventories are in extremely good shape and that points 
positively dederick said 
inventories are watched closely because if they increase without 
a corresponding gain in new orders production cutbacks could occur 
in the future as factories try to get rid of goods stored on 
shelves and backlots 
</TEXT>
