<TEXT>
actors from the la law cosby and 
sesame street tv programs gave their support wednesday to a 
bill that would require all standardsized television sets to be 
able to display captions for deaf or hearingimpaired viewers 
witnesses at a house hearing including tv stars richard dysart 
geoffrey owens and linda bove said millions of americans are being 
excluded from access to broadbased communications systems 
particularly tv 
transmitting socalled closed captioning services on most tv 
sets would benefit not only the estimated 24 million americans with 
hearing disabilities but some 18 million youngsters learning to 
read and millions more foreigners and illiterate adults trying to 
learn english 
i think captioning should be a standard feature on the 
television signal thats how important it is said owens a 
costar on nbctvs cosby show 
a tv manufacturers representative however said it would be 
unfair to require that everyone particularly the poor or 
lowincome senior citizens be required to bear the costs of sets 
with closedcaptioning capability 
the bill by rep major owens dny and a companion measure by 
sen tom harkin diowa would require all sets with screens 13 
inches or larger be able to display captions cost of such 
circuitry has been estimated at 15 to 20 
making such circuitry mandatory amounts to a regressive excise 
tax on all purchasers of television sets in order to benefit a 
small albeit deserving minority said thomas p friel a vice 
president with the electronic industries association 
he urged the house energy and commerce subcommittee on 
telecommunications and finance to require that only some tv sets be 
capable of closedcaptioning 
beginning with the 1989 season abc cbs and nbc were offering 
closedcaptioning on all their primetime programs noted 
subcommittee chairman rep edward markey dmass but witnesses 
said most local and syndicated programs are not closedcaptioned 
and that only 90 of some 1500 local news broadcasts are 
closedcaptioned 
its a cost decision said i king jordan president of the 
gallaudet university school for the hearing impaired he said he 
feared the major television networks would stop offering 
closedcaptioning unless a way was found to enlarge the audience 
for such services 
he said the government already has spent 45 million on 
closedcaptioning since the late 1970s and the closedcaptioning 
bill would ensure that this money will not have been wasted 
dysart who is costar of nbctvs la law and 1990 
chairman of the council for better hearing and speech month 
dismissed the economic arguments he said the prices for the 
closedcaptioning circuitry would drop dramatically when all sets 
had the closedcaptioning circuitry 
dysart said most people cannot afford to buy settop devices 
that currently provide closedcaptioning only about 300000 of the 
settop decoders are in use primarily because of the 160 to 200 
perunit cost he said 
bove of the sesame street childrens show said captioning 
was very important in helping children with normal hearing learn to 
read she said it cost between 1500 and 2000 to caption a 
30minute tv program 
