<DOCNO> AP900502-0118 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the two german states agreed on a treaty for 
merging their economies wednesday after west germany agreed to give 
elderly east germans more financial protection from the throes of 
the free market 
the tentative agreement which still has to be approved by the 
parliaments of both countries settles major differences between 
the two germanys over how to assess the high costs of unification 
it clears the way for a full merger of their economies by july 
2 when the west german mark will become the official currency of 
east germany 
in a major compromise west germany said it would allow senior 
citizens in east germany to convert more of their savings at a 
favorable 11 rate to the west german mark 
the plan comes just three days before a meeting between the two 
germanys and the four world war ii allies that divided germany 
the soviet union united states britain and france to discuss 
the international ramifications of german unity 
us secretary of state james a baker iii was to join foreign 
ministers from the other countries for the historic 
fourplustwo talks in bonn the west german capital 
a full political merger of the two germanys is expected next 
year but first some thorny issues must be resolved including 
membership of a unified germany in nato and new european security 
arrangements 
the economic merger agreement was confirmed wednesday by mathias 
gehler spokesman for east german prime minister lothar de 
maiziere and rudolf seiters chief of staff for west german 
chancellor helmut kohl 
i want to emphasize that what the germanys have agreed upon 
is tied with the responsibility of the economic and social 
developments in both parts of germany and the stability of the 
west german mark seiters said in a statement in bonn 
the two germanys have been negotiating for weeks over how west 
germany can absorb the crippled east german economy without 
threatening the strength of the powerful west german mark 
the east german mark is officially valued at 31 against the 
west german mark but is virtually worthless outside the country 
however east german officials said they needed a nearequal 
conversion rate to make up for removing subsidies which kept down 
prices under the former socialist system 
under the agreement all salaries earned by east germans would 
be converted at a 11 rate the agreement also will allow east 
germans to obtain ownernship shares in stateowned enterprises 
the plan also provides that people aged 60 and older will be 
able to convert up to 3350 in personal savings at the 11 rate 
while east germans 14 and under would be able to convert only up to 
1180 dollars 
everyone else would be able to convert 2300 at the 11 rate 
any savings above the ceiling levels would be changed at a 21 rate 
west germany originally had proposed a 2300 ceiling for all 
germans but east germany demanded a higher limit 
the bundesbank west germanys central bank had advocated a 21 
conversion rate warning that a 11 rate would cost the west german 
economy billions of dollars 
pensioners will receive the most protection under the plan 
elderly east germans will have their monthly pensions raised to 
west german levels when the economies are merged 
west germany also has agreed to allow some stillundefined 
financial protection for students and renters who may not be able 
to afford rents once they are set by the free market 
several protests have been held in recent weeks by east germans 
demanding protection from unemployment and competition from western 
businesses 
east germans who still will earn only about onethird of their 
west german counterparts also fear rising prices when the nations 
are united 
west germans meanwhile fear that absorbing the east german 
economy will dilute the power of the mighty west german currency 
and lead to higher taxes and inflation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

