<TEXT>
banned and vilified by white 
leaders the african national congress has achieved a goal sought 
throughout its 78year history talks with the government on ending 
white domination 
the anc south africas most powerful opposition group began 
meeting with the government wednesday to clear the way for 
negotiations on a constitution that will give the voteless black 
majority a voice in government 
even before the talks began anc leaders described the meeting 
as a triumph for the organization founded in 1912 to fight for 
black political rights 
it is a new lease of life said anc leader reg september 
who returned to south africa last week after 27 years in exile 
we will take full advantage of this and move forward to a new 
south africa 
in this divided country the anc and its close ally the united 
democratic front are the largest political organizations with a 
multiracial leadership 
the ancs rankandfile is overwhelmingly black and male but 
the 11person delegation meeting with the government is comprised 
of six black men two black women two white men and an indian man 
the government side is made up exclusively of male afrikaners 
descendents of dutch who account for 3 million of the countrys 5 
million whites 
the anc has millions of black supporters in south africa and an 
estimated 15000 members in exile many exiles are expected to 
return this year and most observers believe the group would win 
elections if the countrys 28 million blacks were allowed to vote 
several anc rallies have attracted crowds of more than 100000 
people since february when president fw de klerk legalized the 
organization after a 30year ban and freed nelson mandela after 27 
years in prison 
before de klerk assumed power last august government officials 
frequently denounced the anc as a communistinspired terrorist 
group that would be barred from any negotiations 
but de klerk has initiated reforms saying he wants to negotiate 
an end to apartheid which has allowed the white minority to 
maintain political and economic control over blacks 
however he opposes the outright black majority rule favored by 
the anc and other antiapartheid groups 
throughout its history the anc has been led by older 
welleducated blacks who have sought a negotiated solution to the 
countrys race and political conflicts 
albert lutuli anc president in the 1950s and winner of the 
nobel peace prize repeatedly wrote to white leaders requesting a 
meeting the government never consented instead outlawing the 
thenpeaceful anc in 1960 
a year later mandela a lawyer helped launch the ancs 
guerrilla campaign saying it was the only way to oppose apartheid 
most of the leadership was soon arrested or went into exile and 
headquarters were established in lusaka zambia 
the armed struggle which the anc still embraces has never 
posed a serious threat to the government but it has won the 
support of black youths who have received their political education 
in street clashes with security forces 
one of the ancs biggest challenges will be to maintain control 
of its young supporters as the antiapartheid movement moves from 
confrontation to negotiation 
during nationwide unrest in the mid1980s the anc publicly 
stated that it wanted to make south africa ungovernable 
now mandela and other anc leaders are sending mixed signals 
urging supporters to be peaceful and disciplined but saying the 
armed struggle should continue 
in the southeastern province of natal fighting between anc 
supporters and inkatha a relatively conservative zulu group has 
claimed 4000 black lives since 1986 the conflict has intensified 
in recent months despite pleas for peace by both factions and the 
government 
the government has urged the anc to formally suspend its largely 
dormant armed struggle but should the anc do so it would risk 
losing young supporters to more militant groups such as the pan 
africanist congress 
