<TEXT>
an error by a ground controller put the hubble 
space telescope to sleep again overnight but the 15 billion 
instrument was reawakened wednesday and was functioning normally 
again 
it was the third time since the telescope was put into open 
space april 25 that its electronics were powered down to prevent 
damage 
nasa said the controller at the goddard space flight center 
failed to send a signal telling the telescopes lens cover not to 
close during a testing operation the 10foot diameter cover shut 
and its motion caused the telescope to go into a safemode 
the spacecraft operated just as it should have the space 
agency said in a statement the problem was caused by ground 
controller oversight 
in the safemode the telescope automatically maintains its 
position points its solar arrays to the sun to receive power and 
activates other functions to protect the spacecraft 
the system is designed to safeguard the telescope for 72 hours 
without ground control 
it happened the first time on friday when engineers sent 
commands to open the lens cover formally known as the aperture 
door cautious engineers had set the software to accommodate only a 
slight bit of motion and the movement of the door exceeded that 
limit 
the second time was also friday when one of the telescopes two 
highgain antennas was put through its movements a counterweight 
on the dish antenna brushed against a cable and the efforts by a 
motor to overcome the resistance again shut the system down 
the biggest impact of tuesday nights events nasa said was 
that 10 hours in the lengthy startup and calibration process were 
lost but spokesman jim elliott said no delay was expected in 
getting the first picture from the telescope early saturday 
when the telescope first went into its safemode last week the 
recovery process was a lengthy one but nasa said wednesday that 
problems of that nature are expected during a startup process that 
will take more than six months before the first real scientific 
returns 
</TEXT>
