<TEXT>
a federal reserve survey of regional economic 
conditions released wednesday found continued slow growth in april 
and little sign that industrial prices were rising too fast 
overall economic activity continues to expand slowly the 
central bank said in a survey known as the beige book prepared 
by its 12 regional banks for a may 15 monetary policy meeting 
the feds evaluation of the economy was similar to its last two 
surveys in march and january which also reported slow but 
continued expansion and moderate inflation 
however two separate commerce department reports wednesday 
indicate economic activity may be rebounding at a faster pace than 
shown by the fed survey 
the governments index of leading economic indicators jumped 09 
in march the biggest gain in 21 months meanwhile factory orders 
rose 38 percent in march for the largest increase in more than a 
year 
based on the survey alone the fed would appear to be unlikely 
to move interest rates either up or down said economist robert g 
dederick of chicagos northern trust co however fed policymakers 
likely will perceive more danger of inflation than indicated by the 
report he said 
they likely will be especially concerned with consumer prices 
which advanced at an 85 percent annual rate during the first three 
months of this year compared with a 46 percent rate for all of 
1989 he said 
this particular report does not point to the need for any 
tightening of credit this says stay as you are however my 
own view is the odds are they will tighten dederick said 
for most of 1988 and early last year the fed nudged rates 
higher to slow the economy and combat inflation during the last 
half of 1989 it permitted rates to fall in an effort to avoid a 
recession since then its held shortterm rates steady 
in the latest survey most districts report that manufacturing 
which had been particularly affected by the higher rates has 
either improved or is expected to improve despite that no 
general upward pressure on industrial prices is noted it said 
responding to recent concerns expressed by business groups and 
members of congress about a regulatory crackdown on bank lending 
the fed said its regional banks found little evidence that a 
general credit crunch is developing 
however it noted virtually every district cites some 
specific cases of credit tightening by banks with the most 
significant action taken by new england banks still the 
majority of businesses say they have not seen any change in credit 
terms and have not had trouble getting loans 
real estate particularly apartment construction remains weak 
the fed said housing prices continue to fall in the new york 
metropolitan area and in new england but there are pockets of 
strength in parts of california in minneapolisst paul and in 
upstate and western new york 
the central bank survey also pointed to some resilience in the 
consumer sector which accounts for twothirds of the nations 
economic activity 
retail sales reflect slow positive growth apparel 
