<TEXT>
a congressional panel is investigating the 
proposed swap of coalrich wyoming land for a scenic view in grand 
teton national park a deal the panels chairman calls a fire 
sale that will hurt taxpayers 
federal and state governments could lose up to 180 million 
because of the low value interior department officials placed on 
the coal it is trading according to documents compiled by the 
house government operations environment subcommittee 
the department wants to trade a 2500acre tract with 207 
million tons of coal for a conservation easement basically a 
scenic view on a ranch in grand teton park owned by 
businessmanconservationist laurance s rockefeller 
rockefeller has donated the easement to a new york cancer 
institute which would gain the coal tract under the swap 
rockefeller would retain ownership of the land the government gets 
a ban on development preserving the view 
the interior department denied the deal is a bad one for 
taxpayers 
theres no mystery to how we did it said jay guerin a 
spokesman for interiors bureau of land management its the same 
as other evaluations it compares to other kinds of tracts and 
leases involving the federal government 
the committee plans to question interior officials on the deal 
at a hearing thursday panel chairman mike synar dokla is 
questioning the decision to value both the easement and the coal at 
56 million saying the value of the coal is much higher 
synar said wednesday it strains credulity that the 
department valued the 207 million tons of coal it will give up at 
27 cents a ton 
at a time of staggering federal deficits the department of 
the interior should abandon any thought of disposing of publicly 
owned assets at fire sale prices synar said 
the 2500acre youngs creek tract is located near sheridan wyo 
the jy ranch is the largest privately owned section of the park 
rockefeller in 1987 donated the scenic view to the 
sloankettering memorial institute for cancer research 
while the department said 27 cents a ton is the right value for 
undeveloped coal in the ground with no certain market synar 
