<TEXT>
the latvian popular front on wednesday 
unveiled an independence plan that it hopes would bring the baltic 
republic freedom within years without incurring moscows wrath 
deputies from the popular front told an evening news conference 
they believed they had enough votes to get the draft measure passed 
in a session of latvias supreme soviet parliament that opens 
thursday 
the popular front plan would declare independence as a gesture 
but actual independence would occur only after an unspecified 
transition period that deputies estimated would last several years 
estonia like lithuania an independenceminded baltic neighbor 
passed a similar measure march 30 
popular front deputies said they agreed to the measure after 
watching lithuania declare independence march 11 and then struggle 
unsuccessfully to persuade moscow to begin negotiations 
we didnt slam the door and then start to knock said romans 
apsitis a law professor were leaving the door open and still 
moving toward independence 
latvian president anatoly gorbunov expected to be reelected 
thursday said the proposal took into account talks that already 
have begun with moscow 
the session also will vote on dropping the soviet socialist 
from latvias name leaving it simply the republic of latvia 
said deputy janis krumins 
the popular front proposal would leave most of the republics 
sovietera constitution intact but it would also assert latvias 
claim to independence on its historic territory and its right to 
reestablish its traditional parliament 
despite the conciliatory tone of the latvian proposal deputies 
said they were against following the guidelines for secession laid 
down in a soviet law passed in april that makes it difficult for a 
republic to leave the union 
apsitis said at most latvia would consider a role in a 
reconfigured soviet confederation but only after gaining 
independence 
unlike lithuania where native lithuanians make up 80 percent of 
the population native latvians make up about 54 percent of 
latvias 27 million residents the rest are largely russians who 
frown on secession 
despite their ethnic disadvantage latvian nationalists have 
been pushing full force for the parliament to emulate lithuania 
of the 199 members of latvias new supreme soviet elected in 
march 131 are popular front supporters and several more are 
sympathizers a deputy said they need 133 votes for the required 
twothirds majority to pass the independence measure 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev recently warned latvian 
delegates that he would offer the republic special status in a 
reconfigured federation but he would not accept lithuanianstyle 
outright secession 
in the past year latvia has copied lithuanias daring political 
moves in december it abolished the communist partys guarantee on 
power in february it condemned the 1940 act that formalized its 
annexation by the soviet union and last month a large segment of 
its communist party broke off from its moscowbased parent party 
all the moves came within months sometimes weeks of similar 
lithuanian actions 
latvian activists have also created a shadow parliament to 
represent mainly native latvians 
the latvian citizens congress representing 700000 pre1940 
residents and their children convened monday and tuesday to demand 
restoration of the independence the republic lost in 1940 when 
latvia was forcibly annexed by the soviet union along with 
lithuania and estonia 
the congress claims the right to replace the supreme soviet 
during the transition to independence if the parliament votes 
against independence the congress plans to set itself up as an 
alternative authority tass said 
a poll published monday by the soviet newspaper izvestia said 92 
percent of ethnic latvians surveyed favor secession of the 
nonlatvian residents of the republic 45 percent were for 
independence said the poll it did not specify its sample size or 
margin of error 
</TEXT>
