million in financial certificates on wednesday forcing the bank of 
england to come to the london money markets rescue 
although no cash was involved it was a british robbery record 
far above the estimated 48 million haul from a looted london safe 
deposit store in 1987 
the staterun bank of england said it had to inject into the 
money market an amount equivalent to the face value of the stolen 
certificates it said this was to avoid problems for their owners 
and eliminate the risk that a shortage of liquidity would increase 
overnight lending rates 
the bank said a remote chance existed that the certificates 
could be used illegally to secure a bank loan but it would be 
extraordinarily difficult to use the missing paper to raise 
cash 
anyone trying to cash or use these documents would need to 
demonstrate he has good title to them said a bank spokesman who 
refused to be identified 
the bank of england said that within 45 minutes of the robberys 
being reported the bank warned money market firms and banks and 
sent descriptions of the missing property to the london offices of 
foreign central banks to circulate around the world 
police said a briefcase containing the certificates was snatched 
from 58yearold messenger john goddard as he walked from sheppards 
money brokers to another finance house in the city financial 
district 
goddard a longtime employee was unhurt sheppards refused to 
comment police said the robber was black in his late twenties and 
wielded a knife 
unescorted messengers in the densely crowded city have been 
robbed before and the system has often been called archaic 
the bank of england said the messenger system which is more 
than 100 years old was plainly unsatisfactory and by the end 
of this year it expects to have on line a new computerized system 
for settling money transactions 
wednesdays haul consisted of certificates of deposit with a 
face value of 1219 million pounds nearly 200 million and 
treasury bills worth 170 million pounds 278 million that mature 
for payment on july 30 
the paper is regularly traded between banks and some finance 
houses 
certificates of deposit are issued to companies in exchange for 
depositing large amounts of money with a bank or finance house over 
a fixed period and companies can buy and sell them as a way of 
raising money 
treasury bills are a form of iou issued by the government to 
raise shortterm money their face value can be claimed when they 
mature on a fixed date 
in january a city worker found four bond certificates each 
worth 16 million and stated to be as good as cash lying in the 
gutter outside the stock exchange they were handed back to the 
owners 
