<TEXT>
a panel has completed a ranking of 3000 
medical treatments that health officials said wednesday will be 
used to help the state decide what operations are to be eliminated 
from medicaid in the future 
oregon is the first state in the country to consider limiting 
the types of treatments that will be paid for by medicaid 
officials said skyrocketing medical costs have forced the state 
to make a choice either reduce the pool of those who can receive 
medicaid or stop payment on certain expensive treatments like 
transplants it has chosen the latter 
the health services commission compiled a 167page list of of 
3000 medical treatments ranked under a costbenefit formula that 
divides the cost of the procedure by the benefit in years of life 
and improvement of life 
the commission and a panel called oregon health decision 
developed the list after holding 11 public hearings 50 community 
meetings and telephone interviews to find out which illnesses 
oregonians fear the most 
over the next two weeks the committee will weigh aspects such 
as quality of life personal choice and the communitys sense of 
compassion said paige sipesmetzler chairwoman of the 11member 
panel on may 15 it will factor together these criteria with the 
costbenefit analysis to make a final list 
under the current medicaid system the number of people who are 
eligible depends on the amount of money that is available to treat 
them when money gets tight the state rewrites its eligibility 
requirements knocking more people off the medicaid list those who 
are left generally the poorest enjoy a relatively rich package of 
benefits 
the new program while eliminating some services would add 
about 77000 oregonians to basic medicaid rolls that now number 
about 130000 officials said 
the bottom line on which treatments are excluded from medicaid 
will be made by the legislature in january among the most likely 
procedures are transplants which can run into hundreds of 
thousands of dollars 
oregon must get permission from the federal government to modify 
its medicaid program before it can implement the program 
the changes were proposed by state senate president john 
kitzhaber who is an emergency room physician 
in 1987 the legislature halted medicaid funding for most organ 
transplants using the money for other health needs such as 
prenatal care only two other states virginia and arizona exclude 
transplants from medicaid 
congress designed medicaid to provide health care to the poor 
but medical costs have forced states to adjust their eligibility 
standards to exclude many poor people 
other states are watching oregons program to see if they can 
adapt aspects ot it us healthcare spending this year is 
expected to exceed 600 billion about 12 percent of the gross 
national product up from 7 percent in 1970 officials say 
about 315 million people in the united states have neither 
health insurance nor medicaid coverage according to the census 
bureau 
