<TEXT>
a federal appeals court wednesday upheld the 
constitutionality of illinois death penalty statute striking down 
the earlier ruling of a federal judge 
the threemember 7th us circuit court of appeals reversed the 
decision of us district judge harold baker who had ruled in 1989 
that the states death penalty was unconstitutional on the grounds 
that it allowed prosecutors too much leeway on whether to seek 
capital punishment 
some 120 men are on death row in illinois among them is john w 
gacy convicted of killing 33 young men and boys in the worst 
multiplekilling case in us history because of prolonged 
appeals no one has been executed under the 1977 statute 
attorneys for convicted double murderer charles silagy had 
challenged the constitutionality of the law saying their handling 
of the case was hampered by not knowing whether prosecutors would 
seek the death penalty 
the illinois attorney generals office asked the federal appeals 
court in january to overturn bakers ruling 
the 53page decision wednesday by judges michael kanne john 
coffey and frank easterbrook was the first time the federal appeals 
panel has ruled specifically on the current illinois death penalty 
law 
it rejected bakers contention that state laws allowed 
prosecutors to be arbitrary and capricious and thereby hindered 
defense attorneys 
we do not agree wrote kanne in the appellate decision 
instead the law permits the prosecutor to weigh all of the 
evidence kanne wrote in his assessment of the propriety of 
seeking the death penalty 
although illinois prosecutors can wait until after a conviction 
to announce whether they will seek the death penalty they still 
have to prove the case warrants capital punishment kanne said 
assistant illinois attorney general jack donatelli argued before 
the appeals court in january that the state statute was neither 
arbitrary nor capricious but is specific about who is eligible for 
the death penalty and includes safeguards meant to correct any 
mistakes an overzealous prosecutor might make 
wednesdays decision came two days after the us supreme court 
cleared the way for the execution of convicted murderer charles 
walker by ruling that five people who initiated a challenge to 
walkers death sentence had no standing in the case 
walker sentenced to die in 1983 after he pleaded guilty to 
killing sharon winker and kevin paule in southern illinois st 
clair county stands at the top of the list of the states 
deathrow inmates 
walker has said he wants to die and has abandoned all appeals 
the illinois supreme court has yet to set walkers execution date 
</TEXT>
