<TEXT>
the house voted wednesday to limit the federal 
governments spending on the super collider atom smasher to 5 
billion 
current energy department estimates of the ultimate cost of the 
collider range up to 8 billion 
the bill approved 309109 and sent to the senate gives the 
department specific authority to build the particle accelerator 
since the department already could undertake the project under 
other general authority to support scientific research the 
specific authority is important mostly as a sign of political 
support 
the collider a 54milesaround tunnel in which beams of protons 
will smash together to explore the secrets of matter will be the 
largest scientific instrument ever built it is planned for a site 
about 30 miles south of dallas 
under the legislation approved wednesday costs above 5 billion 
would be left to texas which has pledged 1 billion and other 
sources including foreign contributors 
the energy department did not mention the spending limit in a 
statement by deputy secretary henson moore welcoming the house 
action as an important victory 
we are pleased with the 31 margin which demonstrates support 
in congress for this exciting project said moore 
actual spending must be approved in annual congressional 
appropriations the bush administration sought spending authority 
of 318 million for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 up 100 
million from the current year 
robert roe dnj chairman of the science space and 
technology committee said the fiveyear authorization gives the 
collider the stability and continuity that it needs to flourish 
but much of the afternoons debate on the bill centered on 
making sure the federal share would not rise if the total cost of 
the project did 
when the house votes for this legislation today it is going 
on record that the ssc will not cost the taxpayer one dime more 
than 5 billion said rep robert walker rpa the ranking 
minority member of the science space and technology committee 
