<DOCNO> AP900502-0205 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
leaders of us roman catholic bishops have sharply criticized a 
proposed universal catechism prepared by the vatican calling 
parts of it unbalanced out of context and superficial 
its supposed to be a guiding summary of faith but reads too 
much like an encyclopedia the bishops say it needs a more 
positive spirit and should inspire as well as inform 
yet sometimes even the information is distorted the bishops 
say such as in instances implying consensus when consensus is in 
fact lacking 
the proposed document is the first attempt at a churchwide 
doctrinal compilation since 1566 and is regarded as the most 
significant project of the worlds bishops since the second vatican 
council of 196265 
a fundamental problem with the draft is failure to differentiate 
adequately between essential and secondary teachings us bishops 
say the lack of such distinctions can lead to serious 
misunderstanding 
the bishops say the 434page document misuses bible quotations 
in a prooftext manner subordinates the role of the laity 
discounts ecumenical ties with other churches and oversimplifies 
some concepts 
those familiar with the complexity of the issues will judge 
the catechism superficial and may be led to think the same of 
catholic doctrine the bishops say 
they also say the proposed title catechism for the universal 
church is inappropriate and confusing since the document is not 
meant to be a catechism itself but a doctrinal guide for producing 
regional catechisms 
a substitute title is recommended namely a compendium of 
catholic doctrine for the preparation of catechisms 
a commission headed by cardinal joseph ratzinger chief of the 
vaticans doctrinal office drew up the proposed document at the 
behest of a 1985 international synod of bishops 
the draft was distributed sub secreto under secrecy last 
december to the worlds 2500 bishops asking their reactions by 
may 31 
the time alloted for consultation is insufficient the us 
bishops say in their 51page critique asking that the period be 
extended and that later a a second draft be subjected to further 
feedback 
the analysis was prepared by a sixbishop review committee 
headed by bishop oscar h lipscomb of mobile ala in consultation 
with 30 other experts and relayed by the bishops conference to 
the vatican 
individual bishops also were expected to send in their own 
assessments 
the joint response says the proposed document ignores 
contemporary biblical scholarship and principles of interpretation 
and uses new testmanet texts out of context in support of 
particular points 
such an approach would be highly detrimental to catechetical 
and theological practice the bishops say 
this defect works itself out in a deleterious fashion 
throughout the catechism various quotations from scripture are 
cited in a prooftext manner without regard for their proper 
meaning within their proper context 
the bishops also say the document tends to equate central and 
marginal teachings saying 
the text presents doctrines that are not fully certain and are 
peripheral to the faith such as about angels and christs descent 
into hell on the same level as central and certain and defined 
truth the bishops say 
they also questioned the drafts portrayal of jesus as having 
divine infused knowledge leaving little room for his 
developing selfconsciousness on earth 
any possibility of consequence for the humanity of jesus is 
thus excluded the bishops say 
they also say the document seems to establish a false 
separation between science and faith denigrating legitimate 
claims of science the bishops observe pointedly 
the opposition between evolution and creation is obvious only 
if one adopts a fundamentalist point of view toward the creation 
accounts 
concerning lay people the draft seems to cast them in a 
passive receptive role rather than recognizing their active 
initiatives the bishops say 
on this and other matters the draft was seen as reflecting 
attitudes predating reforms of the second vatican council 
regarding the drafts treatment of ecumenical efforts for christian 
unity the bishops say 
as the text stands it tends to emphasize disunity and appears 
to suggest that the principal reason for dialogue is to overcome 
heresy and schism 
the bishops point out another apparent retreat from vatican iis 
view that the christian church subsists in catholicism but 
isnt limited to it the draft says the church has its 
existence in catholicism 
thats close to the terminology the vatican council rejected as 
limiting christianity to catholicism the bishops note implying 
the draft hints a throwback to that insular view 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
