<TEXT>
new englands slumping economy and real estate 
market have pushed many banks to the brink of failure and 
eventually could force them into government hands analysts say 
last week regulators seized control of home owners federal 
savings bank the largest savings and loan in massachusetts 
analysts said tuesday this action was a signal of things to come 
are we going to see a rash of closures in the next few months 
probably not said gerard cassidy a banking analyst at tucker 
anthony inc but when this thing finally washes out three four 
five years from now were going to look back and there probably 
is going to be at least two dozen 
the sinking economy combined with a declining real estate 
market has given many banks a staggering amount of troubled loans 
banks have had to divert money into reserves while watching their 
capital shrink to precarious levels 
james mcfarland deputy regional director of the federal deposit 
insurance corp said there would probably be a handful of 
failures this year 
but he stressed that well below 10 percent of the banks in new 
england have poor ratings from the government 
in massachusetts and connecticut 32 banks at the end of 1989 
were losing money so fast it would deplete their equity within one 
year according to veribanc inc a wakefield mass firm that 
monitors the industry 
its a good bet there will some seizures among them 
especially with the economy going the way it is said warren 
heller research director for veribanc 
analysts say the direction of the economy will be the most 
important factor in determining whether weak banks survive 
bank of new england corp for example lost more than 1 
billion last year due largely to its real estate portfolio the 
bank now is operating under government orders and has instituted a 
plan to improve its financial health but executives have 
acknowledged the recovery hinges on the new england economy 
other banks have admitted they are in peril home national corp 
of milford mass has disclosed its subsidiary home national bank 
is seeking financial assistance from the federal government to 
continue operating 
eliot bank in boston reported a 30 million loss for the fourth 
quarter of 1989 and said it expected regulators to take such 
actions as they consider appropriate if the bank could not raise 
capital 
another teetering company is one bancorp of portland maine 
which has 26 million in capital but 290 million in troubled loans 
one bancorp like many savings banks in new england converted 
to stock ownership in the 1980s amid the boom on wall street that 
provided them with billions of dollars in new capital which many 
used to move into the thenbooming construction market 
the only thing they knew how to do was lend money in real 
estate said james moynihan senior vice president of advest inc 
in boston they were all tripping over each other to find 
projects 
this created several problems for savings banks many had been 
accustomed to home construction lending but felt pressure to move 
into other commercial loans to get better returns and improve their 
shareholder earnings mcfarland said 
but when the real estate market declined poor loans were 
exposed and the losses mounted 
heller at veribanc said some savings institutions were already 
in weak condition before they raised money by converting to stock 
ownership 
this was a onetime capital infusion heller said they 
had their one chance and they blew it 
