<TEXT>
baxter international inc said it cleared the 
sale of a manufacturing plant in israel with the department of 
commerce to avoid the appearance of a conflict with us law 
nevertheless the worlds largest hospital supply company now 
finds itself the target of allegations by a former employee that it 
sold the plant to get off the arab leagues blacklist of companies 
doing business with the jewish state that would violate a us law 
forbidding american companies from participating in foreign 
boycotts 
baxter has agreed to build a similar plant in syria to 
synthesize intravenous body fluids 
baxter spokesman les jacobson said tuesday the company has 
higher hopes for a profitable operation in syria than in israel 
where he said skyrocketing inflation helped make the plant a 
moneyloser 
company officials didnt seek to curry favor with the arabs by 
selling the plant in israel he said 
jewish leaders are demanding an explanation from baxter 
headquartered in deerfield north of chicago 
the issue arose from a memorandum about baxters middle east 
operations that is purportedly on file in the arab leagues boycott 
office in the syrian capitol of damascus the memo suggests the 
1988 sale of the israeli plant and the removal of baxter from the 
arab boycott list were linked 
jacobson said baxter officials repeatedly sought opinions from 
former secretary of state cyrus vance and from the commerce 
department on its middle eastern operations beginning in 1982 
he said baxter had received assurances it was doing nothing 
improper in selling the israeli plant which was built in 1971 and 
employed about 200 people 
because the law is unclear in many respects we felt we needed 
some clearance and guidance jacobson said 
we went to them and said heres what were doing in the 
middle east is this ok they said theyd see no problems with 
that 
the antiboycott law was enacted in 1977 when vance was in 
office to discourage corporations from seeking arab business by 
promising to avoid commerce with israel 
jacobson said the law is murky in defining the conditions 
under which it would be proper for a us company to provide to an 
arab country information about its dealings in israel 
he said baxter probably discussed with syrian government 
officials its plans to sell the israel plant not as a condition of 
being dropped from the arab league blacklist but rather in the 
context of negotiations that resulted in their april 13 agreement 
to jointly build a plant in syria the plant is scheduled to open 
late next year 
jacobson questioned the authenticity of the arab league memo 
copies of which were sent to baxter directors and to the wall 
street journal by dr richard fuisz is a washingtonarea 
businessman and former chief executive officer of baxters middle 
eastern medcom subsidiary 
fuisz sued baxter in 1985 for wrongful termination and 
defamation after he was ousted from his job and demoted jacobson 
said the lawsuit was settled but fuisz reportedly remains bitter 
toward his former employer 
fuisz could not be reached for comment telephone calls to his 
home in great falls va went unanswered 
neither the commerce department nor the securities and exchange 
commission which are reviewing the companys middle east 
activities would comment 
the memo says baxter promised not to do any more business with 
israel 
jacobson said baxter continues to distribute a variety of 
products in israel and has no plans to stop doing so 
the memo implies that we agreed to halt any further commercial 
activity in israel which is flatly untrue jacobson said we 
know very well that would be illegal 
