the government and the airline industry are 
offering 3 million for information leading to the arrest 
conviction or thwarting of air terrorists 
in a move praised by relatives of terrorism victims and endorsed 
by three government agencies the air transport association on 
tuesday added 1 million to a government reward program that 
already totaled 2 million 
and in another joint step tuesday airline officials and the 
federal aviation administration opposed proposed legislation that 
would increase the governments role in inspecting aging airliners 
of the antiterrorism reward ata president robert j aaronson 
said this should be a powerful incentive for people within or 
close to terrorist organizations to reveal plots before they are 
hatched 
aaronson said the airline trade group would match any government 
reward up to 1 million if it involves a threat or attack against a 
us airline and the money also would be available through the fbi 
to match rewards designed to combat domestic air terrorism 
morris d busby state department ambassador for 
counterterrorism said at an ata news conference that rewards 
already have been paid in the governments program but details 
would not be disclosed 
