a year ago the average price of a 20inch 
chain saw of the type used by many farmers was about 365 says the 
agriculture department today the same saw is around 375 
thats an increase of less than 3 percent but it illustrates 
that the creep of inflation is still gnawing at consumers 
including the nations farmers 
overall the departments national agricultural statistics 
service reported this week the april index of prices paid by 
farmers for commodities services interest taxes and hired labor 
was up 34 percent from april 1989 
the agency reports prices for a list of items periodically 
during the year some are listed quarterly others twice a year or 
at other intervals by whatever time period that is used most 
products are currently more expensive than before 
two general exceptions to the price creep according to the 
latest report are prices for field seeds and fertilizer 
for example a year ago the usda said timothy was 8210 per 100 
pounds compared with 132 in april 1989 tall fescue dropped to 
8510 from 111 a year ago and public and common alfalfa seed 
was 157 per hundredweight against the yearearlier price of 180 
the index for fuels and other energy prices was up 16 percent 
from a year ago although some items showed sharp declines from 
earlier this year bulk delivered diesel fuel for example 
averaged 807 cents per gallon in april down 203 cents from 
january but up 1 cent from a year ago 
prices collectively for automobiles and trucks were up 35 
percent from april 1989 although new trucks in the 15 to 2ton 
class and used cars were down slightly all other vehicle prices 
were higher 
feeder livestock prices were up 15 percent from april 1989 the 
report said prices of feeder pigs at 134 per hundredweight were 
up 4150 from january 
for tractors twowheeldrive models in the range of 50 to 59 
horsepower were shown at 17700 each compared with 17300 last 
