rapidly growing imports pushed japans current 
account surplus down 308 percent to 535 billion in the fiscal 
year ended march 31 the finance ministry reported wednesday 
it was the third consecutive year that there has been a decline 
in the surplus in japans current account the widest measure of 
its trade flows 
the surplus was well below the level forecast by government 
economists in february the economic planning agency predicted it 
would register 61 billion 
economists attributed the decline largely to the weak japanese 
yen and its impact on prices 
while a lower yen reduces the value of japanese exports there 
is a time lag before lower prices result in higher volume in 
addition higher crude oil prices measured in dollars added to 
the cost of imports 
for march the current account surplus grew to 81 billion from 
63 billion a year earlier in march 1989 there had been an 
unusual surge in imports before a 3 percent sales tax took effect 
the next month the ministry said 
