bad news on the inflation front a 65 percent annual rate the 
steepest increase since 1981 and up sharply from the 45 percent in 
1989 
interest rates were pushed up starting in december 1988 by the 
federal reserve as it sought to curb inflation by tightening 
credit as inflation seemed to moderate the central bank permitted 
shortterm rates to ease during the second half of 1989 
but many economists now fear the fed may have no choice but to 
retighten credit to keep inflationary pressures under control 
