<TEXT>
if you put your money in a conservative 
highyielding investment that offers convenience liquidity and 
diversification of your money how can you lose 
for one answer to that question ask the legions of people who 
have owned shares of bond funds and other income mutual funds 
through the first four months of 1990 
while these funds which have aggregate assets of 300 billion 
have been earning current yields of 8 percent to 9 percent or more 
from their holdings of such things as treasury securities and 
highgrade corporate bonds their typical total return to 
investors of late has been less than zero 
from jan 1 through april 26 an index of 535 income funds 
calculated by lipper analytical services inc assuming 
reinvestment of dividends showed a loss of 257 percent 
what went wrong for these funds was a rise in the general level 
of longterm interest rates that almost no one had predicted 
going rates on longterm treasury bonds climbed from below 8 
percent at new years to 9 percent in late april 
increasing rates on new fixedincome securities coming to market 
forced the prices of existing bonds downward by about 10 percent or 
more in turn depressing the net asset values of the funds that 
owned those bonds 
yieldconscious investors with a true longterm perspective 
might be inclined to take all this in stride they continue to get 
their current income after all and they retain the hope that 
their principal will recoup its lost value should interest rates 
turn downward again 
but they have no assurance that those hopes will be fulfilled 
within any given period of time the interestrate volatility of 
the late 1970s and 1980s quite apparently has persisted into the 
early months of the 1990s undiminished 
once again an unexpected rise in longterm interest rates 
confounded experts who were anticipating a totally different set of 
events said vincent agnew an investment manager at chicago 
title and trust co 
for people considering new fund investments the latest 
developments have their positive side because of the rise in 
rates their money now can command higher current yields than 
before 
perhaps even more important rates on shortterm securities like 
treasury bills have risen only slightly while longterm rates 
jumped so for the first time in two or three years the yield 
curve representing the range of maturities in the credit markets is 
no longer flat 
thus investors in interestbearing securities are starting to 
see at least some modest extra reward for taking the risk that goes 
with tying up their money for an extended period of time as of the 
beginning of may yields on treasury bonds exceeded yields on bills 
by more than threequarters of a percentage point 
but if that improves the odds a little it still gives no 
assurance of any sure bets for mutualfund investors if longterm 
rates keep rising income funds net asset values will keep losing 
ground 
wright investors service of bridgeport conn argues that 
highquality bonds are attractive right now on the basis of good 
potential for sharply lower yields and higher bond prices by 
yearend 
at chicago title analysts take a warier view the argument 
for lower us interest rates was predicated on a sluggish economy 
accompanied by declining inflationary pressures 
its possible that the consensus view might still prevail but 
dont count on it 
</TEXT>
