<DOCNO> AP900502-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it is still true that the surest way to the top 
of a large american industrial corporation is to find a relatively 
low level job and work your way up 
no it is not a myth 
the myth created in recent decades is that its now more 
common to move into the top job by bouncing from one company to 
another eventually leveraging into the chairmans office 
but eugene jennings examining his research all the way back to 
1939 it is the largest corporate mobility data base of its kind 
finds that it is now far more common to name a chief from within 
the company 
that finding upsets what has become a given in many popular 
accounts of making it to the top but it is conclusive 
jennings who pioneered socalled mobility studies says that 
three out of four individuals named to the top spot in the 1980s 
were what he calls natives compared with only 48 percent in the 
decade of the 1960s 
the professor professor emeritus of management michigan state 
university set out in the late 1940s to study mobility patterns 
or ascendancy routes in industrial america in effect his interest 
was making it in america 
because this was his intent he excluded birth elites and 
privileged elites namely founders children of founders and 
investors and their proxies who probably entered the company by 
raiding it or buying it 
with these exclusions he was able to concentrate on mobility 
patterns and trace the routes to corporate success 
he found that in every category he defined natives were more 
likely than socalled migrants to head americas large industrial 
corporations and that the pattern was becoming even more 
pronounced 
he found for example that natives outscore migrants in every 
age group among the early arrivals or those who achieve the top 
job at 49 years or younger normals age 50 to 575 years and late 
arrivals 58 years or more 
in spite of what some executive recruiters might like to hear 
he found that even when migrants assumed the top job they rarely 
did so without first becoming subordinates and working their way up 
from there 
age and experience he found in his review remain extremely 
important in naming a chief the widely held notion that chief 
executive officers are younger these day is also a myth the fact 
is precisely the opposite 
to illustrate since the 1960s the average age at which chiefs 
are appointed has risen steadily and is now more than 58 years in 
that time the number of younger chief executives has declined 
tenure has risen chiefs remain in the job longer than they used 
to tenure during the 1960s was less than seven years on average 
it is now more than nine years and rising increasingly boards 
waive compulsory retirement rules 
it is a myth too says jennings that corporate boards turn to 
migrant chiefs when the company is in trouble no he says they 
turn to natives the facts suggest older experienced homegrown 
chiefs are treasured by boards 
a popular notion is that more chiefs of us industrial 
companies have had global experience the better to deal with the 
emerging global economy to some extent the impression is false 
jennings found for instance that fewer rather than more chiefs 
have had the experience of living and working abroad for the 
company no he says while they have experience running foreign 
operations theyve done it from home 
as popularly described he says the global manager is a 
myth he finds instead that industrial companies have been 
developing native managers who report to the us office rather 
than sending homeoffice managers abroad 
jennings who for three decades has advised corporate chairmen 
on the grooming of potential successors began his studies with 
live data in 1949 and researched records back to 1939 
from that data have come numerous books including the seminal 
mobile manager in 1964 and routes to the executive suite 
and executives in crisis in the 1970s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900502-0236 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the european communitys executive 
commission proposed measures wednesday to significantly reduce 
pollution from diesel trucks 
carlo ripa di meana ec commissioner for the environment said 
if approved by ec governments and the european parliament the 
proposal would force all trucks in the 12nation trade bloc to cut 
their emissions of carbon dioxide by more than half 
hydrocarbons also would be cut by half and nitrogen oxides by 
slightly less than half making ec diesel trucks as clean as those 
from austria and switzerland 
in the two alpine nations trucks producing more than 82 
decibels are banned between 10 pm and 5 am and ripa di meana 
plans to propose similar curbs on noise pollution this fall 
new antipollution norms will be introduced in austria and 
switzerland on oct 1 1991 ec hauliers were worried the new norms 
would affect their transit through the two nations 
ripa di meana said his proposal had been prepared in full 
consultation with the truck industry these talks had revealed 
that the technology to reduce pollution from diesel engines was 
available in the 12nation trade bloc so new norms could be 
mandatory by oct 1 1991 
ripa di meana said he would also propose legislation to cut the 
amount of sulphur in diesel this fall 
</TEXT>
