<DOCNO> AP900502-0241 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
smirnoff the vodka favored by czars that 
was banished during the russian revolution is back in the ussr 
heublein inc said wednesday it has taken advantage of easing 
eastwest trade restraints to ship smirnoff back to the soviet 
union where it was first distilled in the 1800s 
heublein a liquor and wine company based in farmington has 
been bottling vodka under the smirnoff name in the united states 
for more than 50 years acquiring the formula from russian exiles 
in the 1930s 
peter smirnoff first distilled his vodka in 1818 in moscow and 
through the century became the official supplier of vodka and 
liqueurs to the court of imperial russia heublein spokeswoman 
vivian brooks said 
but the bolshevik party led by vladimir i lenin took control 
of the government in 1917 and moscows businesses and industries 
were seized by the red army 
vladimir smirnoff then running the family distillery was 
jailed and sentenced to death as a symbol of czarist oppression 
smirnoff was rescued by the white army which represented the 
nobility and others opposing the revolution and made his way to 
france in the early 1930s he sold the family formula to rudolph 
kunett another russian exile 
kunett made his way to the united states and set up a vodka 
distillery in bethel later selling the operation to heublein in 
1939 
selling vodka to the soviets might seem a bit like the old joke 
about selling refrigerators to eskimos or bringing coals to 
newcastle but brooks said that from a lifestyle point of view 
russians look to smirnoff as an american symbol which in a way is 
ironic 
heublein launched an advertising campaign tuesday with the theme 
back in the ussr 
the new advertisement is our way of toasting the new openness 
in eastwest relations said charles traynor vice president of 
marketing for heubleins john g martin unit martin bought the 
smirnoff formula and rights for heublein in 1939 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

