<TEXT>
a growing number of major insurers are 
slashing or abandoning personal lines of insurance because of what 
they call declining profits and increased meddling by state 
regulators and lawmakers 
insurance industry analysts say this reduction could spell 
serious trouble for consumers who need automobile homeowners and 
health policies some may be unable to find coverage 
xerox corps crum and forster insurance division announced last 
month that it was exiting the personal insurance market altogether 
joining at least seven others who have reduced or eliminated their 
personal insurance offerings 
those include travelers corp aetna life and casualty co and 
the hartford insurance group in the nations insurance capital 
philadelphiabased cigna corp the new hampshire insurance group 
and continental corp in new york 
insurance executives center much of their frustration on the 
regulation of auto insurance many blame laws such as californias 
proposition 103 which would place restrictions on auto insurance 
premiums and new jerseys new law effectively reducing auto 
insurance premiums 20 percent for the withdrawal from personal 
insurance 
you take any business in any industry and you tell them they 
cant make any money you dont have to be in insurance to know 
what the business will do said david seifer a researcher who 
follows the insurance industry for donaldson lufkin amp jenrette a 
new york investment firm 
its price setting by the legislature said robert brian a 
vice president of hartfordbased conning and co a research firm 
theres only one result and thats total economic chaos the 
arithmetic just doesnt add up theyre destroying the personal 
insurance market 
california new jersey nevada pennsylvania and south carolina 
have all passed laws mandating some sort of a rate rollback the 
massachusetts legislature has been criticized for setting what 
industry experts say are artificially low rates 
on april 30 aetna sued massachusetts claiming a provision of 
the state law that penalizes insurers who want to stop selling auto 
policies there is unconstitutional and amounts to extortion 
there have been threats of rate rollbacks in connecticut and at 
least 15 other states said terry tyrpin assistance vice president 
with the american association of independent insurers an 
illinoisbased group 
joan bianca a crum and forster spokeswoman said regulatory 
restrictions were largely responsible in the companys decision 
threequarters of the companys business is done in states 
undergoing insurance reforms 
hartfordbased travelers corp has withdrawn from the automobile 
insurance field in california affecting 18000 customers the 
company also has stopped writing new policies in new jersey and is 
carefully choosing customers in other states 
the business is extremely competitive profits are very slim 
so we are concentrating on areas we feel are more viable to us 
said dan kaferle a spokesman for travelers we dont see a 
bright future in a business with regulations restricting price 
kaferle said travelers predicted it would have lost about 20 
million between 1989 and 1991 in california where rates have been 
frozen at 1989 levels as lawmakers study proposed legislation the 
company also predicted losses in pennsylvania where auto insurance 
reform is underway 
travelers has also stopped selling new individual majormedical 
health insurance policies 
aetna is scaling down in states where profits are poor the 
company has dropped some independent agents and reduced 
commissions aetna plans to reduce personal auto insurance business 
by 20 percent over the next three years the company also will stop 
selling new individual health insurance policies in may 
the company wrote 18 billion in premiums in 1989 and lost more 
than 80 million said spokesman john hawkins 
weve not thrown in the towel completely said hawkins 
but weve made the decision that we are not going to grow the 
business in those states where we are unprofitable 
insurance analysts say the trend was predictable especially in 
the deteriorating auto insurance field where some states have 
regulated premiums to what the industry calls an unprofitable 
level more companies feeling the squeeze are expected to follow 
suit 
its just the beginning said brian theyve just finally 
run out of hope the multiline companies have decided that they 
cant be everything to everybody 
industry experts say the upheaval means many consumers will find 
it tougher to buy individual health insurance or insurance for 
their cars and homes especially in states where regulation of 
insurance rates is especially stiff or where legislation is pending 
moreover as companies cut back and competition decreases so 
will the quality of insurance said larry kibbee a vice president 
with the alliance of american insurers an insurance industry 
lobbying group 
analysts predict that many consumers will have to fall back on 
substandard insurers getting claims processed may become a 
consumer nightmare they say 
others predict increased rates for some consumers especially in 
states with no restrictions as insurers raise rates to offset 
losses in other areas where rates are regulated 
industry executives assert that the state regulations attack the 
symptom rather than the causes of high rates which they blame on 
problems ranging from fraudulent claims to the high cost of repairs 
and litigation 
legislators are going to have to look more at some of the root 
causes as to why the rates are as high as they are especially in 
the auto insurance industry said kibbee 
last year the alliance did a survey and found for example that 
it cost 60000 for replacement parts for a 1989 nissan maxima with 
a 17000 sticker price said kibbee 
the washingtonbased american insurance association an industry 
lobbying group has been pushing for better laws to keep insurance 
claims out of court dave snyder an official of the organization 
said hefty attorney fees have pushed up insurance rates 
tremendously 
he suggested other solutions like capping medical fees 
increasing automobile safety standards and cracking down on 
traffic violators to reduce accidents 
quick fix solutions like rate roll backs is not going to 
help said terri malenfant a spokeswoman for the alliance of 
american insurers the only way is to hold down the costs of 
repairs medical costs and litigation costs 
kaferle of travelers said artificially low rates will hurt the 
consumer in the long run 
if you hold down those rates for no other reason other than to 
hold down rates eventually all those costs will have to catch up 
with the consumers and they are going to have a major rate shock 
he said 
