<TEXT>
soybean futures prices resumed their 3monthold rally wednesday 
as traders ignored bearish supply factors and again took their cues 
from price movement charts that suggested the market had room to 
move higher 
grain futures also rose sharply on the chicago board of trade 
while on other markets oil copper and precious metal futures fell 
and most livestock and meat futures advanced 
soybean futures settled 6 cents to 9 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in may up 9 cents at 636 a bushel 
wheat futures settled 4 cents to 6 cents higher with may at 
373 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 4 cents higher with may at 
287 a bushel oats were 3 cents to 6 cents higher with may at 
168 a bushel 
the price of soybeans for nearterm delivery has risen about 15 
percent since jan 9 when the market began its climb from 553 a 
bushel 
the buying has been spurred at times by fundamental factors such 
as brazilian soybean harvesting delays and strong domestic demand 
for soybean meal 
but observers said the powerful advance of the past week 
totaling about 27 cents in the last six trading sessions has been 
led by speculators that trade according to their interpretation of 
price charts known as technical analysis 
based on the charts analysts said the market looked ripe for a 
rally wednesday after tuesdays modest decline funds operated by 
the big trading companies tudor investment corp and refco inc 
were said to be big buyers despite forecasts for beneficial rain in 
the midwestern corn and soybean belt and indications that the 
brazilian soybean harvest is advancing rapidly 
it was a purely chartdriven market said william 
biedermann director of research for allendale inc a chicagoarea 
trading firm 
if you want to come up with a fundamental reason youd have 
to dream something up like anticipation of adverse weather and 
stronger export demand but thats really fishing for something 
he said 
the wheat market was supported by some fundamental news the 
agriculture department announced wednesday morning that it had 
targeted china for sales of 2 million metric tons of us wheat at 
subsidized prices 
wheat futures also were boosted by concerns that heavy rains in 
texas and oklahoma could cause winter wheat harvest delays and crop 
losses analysts said 
oil futures dipped on the new york mercantile exchange erasing 
early gains after opec ministers meeting in geneva postponed a 
second full plenary session about ways to cut their oil production 
and raise crude oil prices 
the ministers meeting in emergency session were finding it 
difficult to agree on how much to trim production and how to 
allocate the cuts among cartel members sources told the associated 
press 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 21 cents 
lower with june at 1868 a barrel heating oil was 89 cent to 
112 cents lower with june at 5185 cents a gallon unleaded 
gasoline was unchanged to 15 cent lower with june at 6095 cents a 
gallon 
copper futures ended lower on new yorks commodity exchange 
following reports that the peruvian government had ordered back to 
work employees of the southern peru copper corp who have been on 
strike since march 12 
copper settled 60 cent to 15 cents lower with may at 1213 a 
pound 
also on the commodity exchange gold futures settled 70 cents to 
80 cents lower with june at 372 a troy ounce silver was 25 cents 
to 3 cents lower with may 4988 a troy ounce 
