<TEXT>
president carlos salinas de gortari on 
wednesday proposed a constitutional amendment to reopen banking to 
private ownership but said the government would retain some 
nationalized commercial banks 
the president said his proposal to congress for the amendment 
reflected the economic changes since president jose lopez portillo 
nationalized the nations 35 private banks in 1982 at the outset of 
mexicos financial crisis 
lopez portillo claimed the banks were helping mexicans get money 
out of the country worsening an economic recession 
circumstances have changed salinas said in a communique 
the development policies have been modified and transcendental 
transformations have been carried out in the economic structures 
the country has made an enormous effort to overcome the crisis 
and at the same time to respond to the challenges of the last 
decade of the 20th century to respond with justice to the demands 
of society and confront with sovereignty a transformed more 
competitive technologically revolutionized world of still 
uncertain perspectives 
since lopez portillo nationalized the banks the banking system 
has been reopened to 34 percent ownership by private investors 
independent government agencies or corporations a presidential 
spokeswoman said that under the salinas proposal 100 percent 
private ownership would be possible 
salinas bill faces a tougher time in congress than the 
constitutional amendment that allowed the nationalization 
in 1982 the institutional revolutionary party or pri held a 
twothirds majority in congress and rubberstamped presidential 
bills it lost that advantage in 1988 when salinas won by the 
slimmest presidential margin in the partys 60year history 
leftist parties which oppose salinas program to privatize 
stateowned industry and business quickly criticized the bill 
ricardo pascoe pierce of the democratic revolutionary party the 
largest leftist party said the proposal was a ploy to try to win 
popularity in national and foreign financial circles 
with 123 of the 500 seats in the lower house they could not 
defeat the bill but are likely to try to slow it down and arouse 
nationalistic sentiment 
support for the bill is likely from the probusiness national 
action party the pri reached a deal with the party in 1989 to pass 
electoral reforms 
salinas has sold or put up for sale major companies including 
the national airline steel mills and its stock in the telephone 
monopoly but he had not yet ventured into sectors set aside for 
the government in the constitution including banking oil and 
electricity 
he skirted the constitution in the petrochemical area 
reclassifying some basic petrochemicals to secondary thus allowing 
private and foreign investment 
salinas said many of mexicos social needs can be met with money 
the government no longer will spend on banking and with money 
raised by the sale of bank stock 
under the bill the state proposes that it not be the majority 
owner of each and every one of the banking institutions he said 
however it will retain a participation in commercial banking and 
will strengthen those institutions oriented to development of 
specific priority activities 
a presidential statement noted that france and portugal among 
other countries had made similar banking reforms and that eastern 
european countries were preparing similar changes 
salinas did not mention foreign banks and it was not immediately 
clear how or if they would be affected 
one foreign banker who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
the proposal was very fuzzy and did not ensure that existing 
banks would be sold 
eduardo garcia suarez president of the national association of 
chambers of commerce said the country needs an exclusively 
private rather than mixed system to be able to compete 
internationally the government news agency notimex said 
</TEXT>
