<TEXT>
control data corps new chief executive told 
shareholders wednesday he has purged the computer company of 
bureaucracy wasteful spending and arbitrary bonuses 
at an annual meeting punctuated by shareholder criticism of 
multimilliondollar severance and retirement packages lawrence 
perlman said changes in the companys culture should lead to 
consistent profitability 
the control data of the past was not always a company that 
thought in terms of building shareholder value said perlman who 
became chief executive in january after the company posted a net 
loss of 680 million in 1989 
he said stockholders employees and customers have been asked to 
endure a great deal during the last five years in which the 
company lost 15 billion 
but perlman defended the companys board for signing a contract 
in 1986 that gave former company head robert price 531 million in 
severance retirement and bonus money price also will get 450000 
a year under a threeyear consulting contract and receive a 
300000 annual pension 
two shareholders took the floor at the meeting to criticize 
prices contract and previous large payouts to retiring senior 
executives 
im outraged said edward diesing a former control data 
employee who termed the compensation exorbitant payoffs and 
payola 
its called greed said diesing who was applauded by fellow 
shareholders there is way too much of this attitude in the us 
and quite possibly at control data what do you think happens to 
employees morale when these disturbing sins are reported 
perlman said prices contract was reasonable at the time it 
was signed four years ago but senior executives signing such 
agreements today are entitled to less he said 
for instance senior executives no longer are entitled to 
severance payments if they leave voluntarily perlman said 
price announced last month that he would not stand for 
reelection to the companys board of directors the company lost 
924 million during his fouryear reign 
perlman said all consulting contracts at the company are under 
review because some have been abused and he said no employees 
will receive bonus money unless they achieve profits for the 
company 
in some cases under the old bonus system payments were quite 
subjective he said i want people to be able to produce a 
number perlman said 
in his remarks to shareholders perlman made repeated references 
to control datas past once selfdescribed as the worlds most 
innovative company control data grew wildly and profited in the 
1960s and 70s before stumbling in the 80s 
buoyed by the large gross margins of the 1970s and the early 
1980s the company did not build into its culture the discipline of 
constant attention to controlling expenses and reducing costs 
perlman said 
he said corporate overhead was out of hand several years 
ago but has been controlled by a reduction in corporate staff to 
250 from about 3000 in 1985 
people are beginning to treat the companys money as if it 
were their own he said 
he also said investment decisions will be based on financial 
analysis and reasonable expectations of returns on investment not 
on hope not on emotion 
perlman and price last year shut down control datas 
supercomputer subsidiary eta systems at a cost about 335 million 
control data founder william c norris who headed the company 
until 1986 and still sits on the board of directors said he wasnt 
offended by perlmans portrayal of the companys past 
i didnt take it personally norris said after the meeting 
the company had problems from time to time the thing that hurt 
us more than anything else was the japanese 
analysts have predicted control datas net income for 1990 at 1 
a share to 150 a share perlman said he is not comfortable with 
the prediction beyond the midpoint of that range 
