<TEXT>
former ashland oil co chairman orin atkins 
testified wednesday that he never personally benfited from a scheme 
to sell confidential ashland documents to irans national oil 
company 
atkins took the stand in the us district court trial of 
attorney charles barnett 38 of palm beach fla who is charged 
connection with the 1979 conspiracy atkins pleaded guilty to 
related charges last september and agreed to cooperate 
i never received any money from any iranian at any time 
atkins said 
in opening arguments monday assistant us attorney herve 
gouraiage described barnett as an instrumental player in the 
conspiracy to sell the documents to the iranian national oil 
company for use in a civil lawsuit against ashland 
barnett was the person who thoroughly familiarized himself 
with the contents of the stolen ashland documents so he could 
explain their usefulness to the iranians gouraiage said 
the papers dealt with the 1979 sale of 283 million of crude oil 
from the iranian company to a subsidiary of the kentucky oil 
concern ashland overseas trading ltd 
iran sued ashland in 1985 for not paying for the oil and 
ashland settled the case last year by agreeing to pay 325 million 
prosecutors said atkins initiated the plan in 1982 after being 
forced to resign his executive position in 1981 he continued to 
work for ashland as a highly paid consultant until 1984 
atkins in his guilty plea admitted that he improperly obtained 
259 corporate documents and tried to sell them to the iranians in 
return for a cut of any damages iran won in the lawsuit 
on the witness stand atkins said he and others involved in the 
deal also tried to sell his consulting services which would have 
involved identifying ashland employees who were potential witnesses 
in the lawsuit 
he said he met only once in 1982 with unofficial 
representatives of the iranian company atkins said negotiations 
with the iranians were handled by former ashland consultant roy 
furmark barnett and others 
furmark who also will testify pleaded guilty in the scheme in 
march he admitted showing some of the documents to representatives 
of the iranian company at a meeting in london 
atkins faces up to 10 years in prison and a 500000 fine when 
sentenced later this year for conspiracy and wire fraud 
the first witness at barnetts trial was dustan mccoy an 
ashland attorney who said the company had refused to pay iran for 
the oil because it believed iran had breached the contract 
barnetts attorney marvin segal told the jury in opening 
remarks that barnetts actions were part of a legal enterprise to 
help the iranian oil company collect the money it avowedly was 
owned 
the indictment against barnett said he atkins and others made 
numerous attempts to sell the documents to the iranians between 
1982 and 1988 prosecutors have not said whether the iranians 
bought any documents 
furmark was a marginal participant in the irancontra scandal 
and gave testimony during investigations by house and senate 
committees and special prosecutor lawrence walsh 
barnetts attorneys are seeking to obtain transcripts of 
furmarks testimony about the irancontra affair to use in 
barnetts defense 
us district judge john e sprizzo has said he will review the 
testimony before ruling on its admissibility as evidence 
</TEXT>
