<DOCNO> AP900502-0272 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mayor tom bradley on wednesday proposed 
mandatory conservation measures requiring all water customers to 
cut use by 10 percent from 1986 levels to cope with californias 
worsening drought 
the state is experiencing its fourth consecutive drought year 
and the situation is serious bradley said at a news conference 
at city hall 
the regional metropolitan water district which provides about 
half the water needed by 15 million people in southern california 
has forecast a 10 percent shortfall in its supplies this summer 
the citys department of water and power which is getting 60 
percent of its water supply from the metropolitan water district 
this year serves 34 million residents 
the mayors request was a judgment call said james f 
wickser the departments water chief available water supplies for 
the city appear adequate at least through december and consumption 
last month was 14 percent below april 1989 wickser said 
bradley said there is a need to step up a voluntary water 
conservation program in effect since 1988 
although the measures bradley proposed are the most restrictive 
since the states record drought of 1977 they pale in comparison 
to those in santa barbara where officials are trying to cut water 
use by 45 percent 
in a letter to the city council bradley sought changes in a 
1977 drought ordinance that set out five increasingly stringent 
steps for conservation 
council approval likely will take six weeks at least mayoral 
aides said 
we can no longer delay in informing the citizens of los 
angeles that because of the lengthy statewide drought we have no 
choice but to require waterreducing actions by every resident 
business and corporation bradley said in a statement 
council president john ferraro agreed that the measures are 
needed and said the proposal has already been scheduled for the 
appropriate council committee 
the twoyearold city drought ordinances first phase calls for 
a voluntary 10 percent cutback it forbids people from hosing down 
sidewalks and driveways and restaurants and hotels from routinely 
serving drinking water it has not been widely observed or 
enforced although the department of water and power reported total 
water use last summer fell about 8 percent 
commonplace first phase violations prompted the mayor to seek 
the mandatory 10 percent reduction aides said 
the mayor also recommended a ban on watering gardens and lawns 
between 10 am and 5 pm and prohibiting water from overflowing 
onto sidewalks or streets 
bradleys proosal would assess surcharge penalties for excess 
water use 
the bimonthly bill for an average residential customer who fails 
to cut water use by 10 percent would jump from about 50 to about 
70 on the first offense said john stodder a mayoral aide 
additional penalties would be heaped on customers who continue 
to use too much water including the installation of water flow 
restriction devices or a service shutoff for repeat offenders 
under existing law a city council resolution is needed to 
implement the penalty aspects of the conservation ordinance 
the mayor said that those who voluntarily have cut back 10 
percent of their 1986 water use when water was plentiful would 
not be required to make additional reductions 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

